{"title_page": "V. K. Singh", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian politician and former army general}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = '''[[The Honourable]]''' <br> [[General (India)|General]]\n| honorific-suffix = [[Param Vishisht Seva Medal|PVSM]], [[Ati Vishisht Seva Medal|AVSM]], [[Yudh Seva Medal|YSM]], [[Aide-de-camp|ADC]], [[Member of parliament, Lok Sabha|MP]]\n| image = [[File:General Vijay Kumar Singh.jpg|200px]]\n| alt = V K Singh\n| office = [[Ministry of Road Transport and Highways|Minister of State for Road Transport and Highways]]\n| primeminister = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| term_start = 30 May 2019\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Mansukh L. Mandaviya]]\n| successor = \n| office1 = [[Minister of External Affairs (India)|Minister of State for External Affairs]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Deepak Kapoor]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| successor1 = [[V. Muraleedharan]]\n| office3 = [[Ministry of Statistics and Programme Implementation|Minister of State (Independent Charge) for Statistics and Programme Implementation]]\n| predecessor3 = [[Rao Inderjit Singh]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| successor3 = [[D. V. Sadananda Gowda]]\n| party = [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n| office2 = [[Ministry of Development of North Eastern Region|Minister of State (Independent Charge) for Development of the North Eastern Region]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Paban Singh Ghatowar]]\n| successor2 = [[Jitendra Singh (BJP politician)|Jitendra Singh]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1951|5|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Bhiwani]], [[East Punjab|Punjab]], [[India]]<br />(now in [[Haryana]], [[India]])\n| nationality = [[Indian People|Indian]]\n| alma_mater = [[National Defence Academy (India)]]<br />[[Indian Military Academy]]<br />[[Defence Services Staff College]]<br />[[United States Army War College]]\n| term_start1 = 26 May 2014\n| term_end1 = 30 May 2019\n| term_start2 = 26 May 2014\n| term_end2 = 9 November 2014\n| term_start3 = 9 November 2014\n| term_end3 = 5 July 2016\n| office4 = [[Lok Sabha|Member of Parliament, Lok Sabha]]\n| term_start4 = 16 May 2014\n| term_end4 = \n| constituency4 = [[Ghaziabad (Lok Sabha constituency)|Ghaziabad]]\n| predecessor4 = [[Rajnath Singh]]\n| majority4 = 501,500 (61.96%)\n| successor4 = Incumbent\n| office5 = 24th [[Chief of Army Staff (India)|Chief of the Army Staff]]\n| president5 = [[Pratibha Patil]]\n| primeminister5 = [[Manmohan Singh]]\n| term_start5 = 31 March 2010\n| term_end5 = 31 May 2012\n| predecessor5 = [[Deepak Kapoor]]\n| successor5 = [[Bikram Singh (general)|Bikram Singh]]\n| nickname = \n| allegiance = {{flag|India}}\n| branch = {{army|India}}\n| serviceyears = 14 June 1970 - 31 May 2012\n| rank = [[File:General of the Indian Army.svg|20px]] [[General (India)|General]]\n| servicenumber = IC-24173<ref name=\"commission\"/>\n| unit = [[Rajput Regiment]]\n| commands = [[Chief of the Army Staff (India)| Chief of Army Staff]] <br />[[Eastern Command (India)|Eastern Army]]<br />[[II Corps (India)|II Corps]]<br />Victor Force, [[Rashtriya Rifles]]<br/>168th Infantry Brigade<br/> 2nd Btn. [[Rajput Regiment]] (Kali Chindi)\n| battles = [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971]]<br/>[[Operation Pawan]]<br/>[[Kargil War]]\n| awards = [[File:Param Vishisht Seva Medal ribbon.svg|33px]] [[Param Vishisht Seva Medal]]<br/>[[File:Ati Vishisht Seva Medal ribbon.svg|33px]] [[Ati Vishisht Seva Medal]]<br />[[File:Yudh Seva Medal ribbon.svg|33px]] [[Yudh Seva Medal]]<br />[[File:Ranger Tab.svg|33px]] [[Ranger Tab]]\n}}\n\n[[General (India)|General]] '''Vijay Kumar Singh''', {{small|[[Param Vishisht Seva Medal|PVSM]], [[Ati Vishisht Seva Medal|AVSM]], [[Yudh Seva Medal|YSM]], [[Aide-de-camp|ADC]], [[Member of parliament, Lok Sabha|MP]]}} (born 10 May 1951) is an Indian politician and a retired [[Four-star rank|four-star]] General in the [[Indian Army]]. Since May 30, 2019, he is serving as the [[Minister of State]] for [[Ministry of Road Transport and Highways|Road Transport and Highways]] in the [[Second Modi ministry]]. He previously served as [[Minister of State]] for [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|External Affairs]] in the [[First Modi ministry]] and as [[Minister of State (Independent Charge)]] for [[Northeast India|Development of the North-Eastern Region]].\n\nDuring his military career, Singh served as the 23rd [[Chief of Army Staff (India)|Chief of the Army Staff]] from 2010 to 2012. Singh took the  [[Government of India]] to court in a dispute over his date of birth and subsequent retirement, becoming the first serving Indian [[Chief of the Army Staff (India)|military Chief of Staff]] to take legal action against the Indian government.\n\nAfter his retirement from the military, Singh joined the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) in 2014 and was elected [[Member of Parliament (India)|Member of Parliament]] of the [[Lok Sabha]] for the [[Ghaziabad (Lok Sabha constituency)|Ghaziabad constituency]] of [[Uttar Pradesh]]\nin [[2014 Indian general election|that year's general election]]. He was re-elected to the same seat in [[2019 Indian general election|2019]].\n\nSingh has written an autobiography called ''[[Courage and Conviction]]''.\n\n==Early life and education==\nGeneral Vijay Kumar Singh was born in [[Bapora]] village in the state [[Haryana]]. His father was a Colonel in the Indian Army and grandfather a [[Junior Commissioned Officer]]. Singh was educated at [[Birla Public School]] in [[Pilani]], [[Rajasthan]]. He is an alumnus of [[National Defence Academy (India)|National Defence Academy]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20100124/main6.htm|title=Bapoda village basks in Gen VK Singh\u2019s glory|last=Mohan|first=Raman|date=24 January 2010|publisher=The Tribune |accessdate=2010-04-03 |location=Chandigarh}}</ref>\n\n==Military career==\nSingh was commissioned into the 2nd Battalion of the [[Rajput Regiment]] (Kali Chindi) on 14 June 1970.<ref name=\"commission\"/> He commanded the same unit when it was positioned along the [[Line of Control]] with Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dutta|first=Sujan|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1110730/jsp/nation/story_14309462.jsp |title=Generation shift in air force |date=30 July 2011 |work=The Telegraph |accessdate=2012-03-26}}</ref>\n\nHe graduated from the [[Defence Services Staff College]]. He was an honours graduate of the [[United States Army Infantry School]], a graduate of the [[Ranger School|Rangers Course]] at [[Fort Benning]] and the [[United States Army War College]] in [[Carlisle, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=DNA20100331>{{cite news |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report_gen-vk-singh-battles-odds-becomes-26th-army-chief_1365552 |title=Gen VK Singh battles odds, becomes 26th army chief |publisher=DNA |date=31 March 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-26}}</ref>\n\nSingh is experienced in both [[counter-insurgency]] and [[Mountain warfare|high-altitude]] operations. He also saw action as a young [[Lieutenant]] in the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971]] while serving as an intelligence officer of 2 [[Rajput Regiment|Rajput]].{{citation needed|date=April 2015}} During his career he has served in various positions:\n* Instructor in the [[Indian Military Training Team]] (IMTRAT) headquarters in [[Bhutan]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Courage and conviction : an autobiography |isbn=9789382277576 |page=122}}</ref>\n* Instructor at [[Army War College, Mhow|Infantry School]] twice and Chief Instructor at JLW (Commando Wing), [[Belgaum#Defence training centres|Belgaum]].<ref name=saisam10>{{cite news|title=Change of Guard - General VK Singh new COAS|url=http://sainiksamachar.nic.in/englisharchives/2010/apr16-10/h1.htm|accessdate=2014-06-15|publisher=Sainik Samachar|date=10 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Did you know: Gen VK Singh is a small time movie star!|url=http://www.firstpost.com/india/did-you-know-gen-vk-singh-is-a-small-time-movie-star-190673.html|accessdate=2014-06-15|publisher=First Post|date=23 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=When the army chief did a cameo in Bollywood|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/When+the+army+chief+did+a+cameo+in+Bollywood/1/91040.html|accessdate=2014-06-15|publisher=India Today|date=3 April 2010}}</ref>\n* Military Operations Directorate at the Army Headquarters.\n*Served as [[Commanding Officer|CO]] 2 Rajput, the battalion he was commissioned in.\n*Served as the Colonel General Staff (Col GS) of 12 Infantry Division\n*Commanded the 168 Infantry brigade at [[Samba, Jammu|Samba]].<ref name=saisam10/><ref name=is10>{{cite news|title=Gen V K Singh takes over as Army Chief|url=http://www.indiastrategic.in/topstories556.htm|accessdate=2014-06-15|publisher=India Strategic|date=31 March 2010}}</ref>\n* Brigadier General Staff (BGS) of [[Jalandhar]] based [[XI Corps (India)|XI Corps]] during [[Operation Parakram]] when Indian troops were mobilised on the border in the wake of the attack on the Indian Parliament in 2001.\n* Commanded the Victor Force, part of the [[Rashtriya Rifles]].\n* Commanded [[Ambala]]-based [[II Corps (India)|II Corps]].\n* Commanded the Army's [[Eastern Command (India)|Eastern Command]].\n\nSingh became the 24th Chief of Army Staff on 31 March 2010, and was the first commando to achieve that position.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiastrategic.in/topstories556.htm|title=Gen V K Singh takes over as Army Chief|date=March 2010|website=India Strategic|accessdate=2014-05-27}}</ref> Towards the end of his career there was a dispute regarding his date of birth, causing him to become the first serving officer of the Indian Army to take the government to court.<ref name=NDTV20120326>{{cite news|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/army-chief-discloses-offer-of-rs-14-crore-bribe-cbi-inquiry-ordered-189957|accessdate=2012-03-26 |title=Details of who allegedly offered Rs. 14-crore bribe to Army chief |first=Nitin A.|last=Gokhale|work=NDTV|date=26 March 2012}}</ref> As a consequence of an error made when he had enrolled with the [[National Defence Academy]] in 1965, official records misstated the year in which he was born. He withdrew the writ in February 2012 when, according to ''[[The Hindu]]'', the [[Supreme Court of India]] \"refused to intervene\". The Court noted that there was no dispute regarding his actual date of birth and that the matter being contested was regarding how that had been recorded. It ruled that Singh had on three occasions accepted the misrecorded date.<ref name=\"The Hindu 20120210\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article2878671.ece |title=Army Chief loses age war |publisher=The Hindu|date=10 February 2012|accessdate=2012-02-11 |first=J. |last=Venkatesan}}</ref>\n\nThe [[BBC]] noted in 2012 that defence experts considered a drive to modernise the Indian army had suffered from \"a lack of planning and acrimony between the military and the defence ministry\". This report followed an interview given by Singh in March 2012 that had caused a political row. Singh said that over a year earlier he had reported to [[A. K. Antony]], the defence minister, that he had been offered a bribe of {{USD}}2.7 million if the army bought several hundred sub-standard vehicles. Antony issued a rebuttal to the interview, saying that he had requested at the time that Singh provide a written report regarding the incident and that this had never been submitted. Two days after the interview with Singh, correspondence between the general and the [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]], [[Manmohan Singh]], was leaked. This criticised the standard of India's defences and caused a further political row.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-12769214 |title=India's corruption scandals |publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\nSingh retired as Chief of Army Staff on 31 May 2012. He was succeeded by General [[Bikram Singh (soldier)|Bikram Singh]].<ref>{{cite news| url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article3474071.ece |title = Gen. V.K. Singh to retire today|work==The Hindu|date=31 May 2012 |accessdate=2012-05-31}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nSubsequent to his retirement from the military, Singh showed support for the [[2012 Indian anti-corruption movement|anti-corruption movement]].<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article3723926.ece|title=V.K. Singh: throw the corrupt out of power |date= 4 August 2012}}</ref> He was seen on the stage in August 2012 at the [[Ramlila Maidan]] in [[New Delhi]], where [[Ramdev]] was fasting in protest of alleged black money and corruption. He was reported to have declared that \"It is shocking but true that over two lakh farmers have committed suicide since 1995. The problems of farmers will have to take the forefront in this movement as the government has turned a blind eye to their woes.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Mohammad |last=Ali |title=Ramdev takes on Congress, warns of march to Parliament |work=The Hindu |date=13 August 2014 |url =http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/ramdev-takes-on-congress-warns-of-march-to-parliament/article3757648.ece}}</ref> Around that time he also compared the movement, whose principal figurehead was [[Anna Hazare]], to that of the [[Bihar Movement]] that had been led by [[Jayaprakash Narayan]] in 1975. He said that \"When I evaluate the country's present condition, it is similar to that of 1975. Jayaprakash Narayan had then said ''Vacate the throne, common people are coming''. He felt then that corruption is the root of all problems&nbsp;... the situation in the country is the same today\".<ref>{{cite news |agency=ANI |title =VK Singh now battles with Baba Ramdev |work=Zee News |date=12 August 2012|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/nation/vk-singh-now-battles-with-baba-ramdev_793178.html}}</ref>\n\n[[File:GNLU VC with VK Singh.jpg|thumb|right|250px|V.K Singh at an International conference at the Center for Foreign Policy and Security Studies, [[Gujarat National Law University]]]]\nSingh led an agitation with Yoga Guru [[Ramdev]] on 23 December 2012, at [[Jantar Mantar]], New Delhi, on the [[2012 Delhi gang rape case]]<ref>{{cite news |agency=PTI |title=V K Singh, Baba Ramdev named in FIR for violence at Jantar Mantar |work=Financial Express |date =24 December 2012 |url=http://www.financialexpress.com/news/v-k-singh-baba-ramdev-named-in-fir-for-violence-at-jantar-mantar/1049641}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=V K Singh, Ramdev named in FIR for violence at Jantar Mantar |work=Times of India|date=24 December 2012 |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/videos/news/V-K-Singh-Ramdev-named-in-FIR-for-violence-at-Jantar-Mantar/videoshow/17745058.cms }}</ref>\n\nSingh joined the Bharatiya Janata Party on 1 March 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Former Army Chief Gen. V K Singh joins BJP along with other Officers |url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/03/former-army-chief-gen-v-k-singh-joins-bjp-along-with-other-officers/ |agency=IANS |date=1 March 2014 |work=Bihar Prabha |accessdate=2014-03-01}}</ref> He won the [[Ghaziabad (Lok Sabha constituency)]] seat in the 2014 Indian general election, defeating [[Raj Babbar]] of the [[Indian National Congress]] by a margin of 567,260 votes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sinha |first1=Arunav |title=Former chief of Army staff General (retired) VK Singh defeats Raj Babbar of Congress by 567260 votes to register a win at Ghaziabad. |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/Former-chief-of-Army-staff-General-retired-VK-Singh-defeats-Raj-Babbar-of-Congress-by-567260-votes-to-register-a-win-at-Ghaziabad-/articleshow/35217329.cms? |accessdate=15 January 2017 |work=The Times of India |agency=TNN |date=16 May 2014 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170115204357/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/Former-chief-of-Army-staff-General-retired-VK-Singh-defeats-Raj-Babbar-of-Congress-by-567260-votes-to-register-a-win-at-Ghaziabad-/articleshow/35217329.cms? |archivedate=15 January 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He was re-elected in a landslide during the [[2019 Indian general election]].\n\n===Union minister===\nIn May 2014, Singh was appointed as Minister of State of External Affairs and Minister of state (independent charge) for North East Region in the NDA-led Indian Government.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/list-of-ministers-in-narendra-modis-government/articleshow/35626035.cms |title=List of ministers in Narendra Modi's government |work=Economic Times |date=27 May 2014 |accessdate=2014-06-07}}</ref> He was relieved of responsibility for the North East Region in November 2014, when Jitendra Singh replaced him.<ref>{{cite news |title=What went wrong? VK Singh lost Doner to MoS for personnel Jitendra Singh |first=Aman |last=Sharma |date=11 November 2014 |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/what-went-wrong-vk-singh-lost-doner-to-mos-for-personnel-jitendra-singh/articleshow/45104244.cms |work=Economic Times |accessdate=2015-04-21}}</ref> He has held the office of Minister of State (Independent Charge) under the Statistics and Programme Implementation portfolio in the NDA government.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nSingh is praised for leading [[Operation Raahat]], a rescue mission to evacuate Indian citizens and other foreign nationals from [[Yemen]] during 2015 [[Yemeni Crisis (2011\u2013present)|Yemeni Crisis]].<ref name=hindu-evac>{{cite news|title=India begins evacuating citizens|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/india-begins-evacuating-citizens/article7054994.ece|publisher=The Hindu|date=31 March 2015|accessdate=2015-03-31}}</ref> Prime Minister Narendra Modi in April 2015 said, \u201cI believe this is the first time in the world that a government minister has stood on the battlefield like a soldier to do this work&nbsp;... I salute General V. K. Singh.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|title=Presstitutes remark row: PM Narendra Modi says media ignoring V K Singh\u2019s good work in Yemen|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/pm-salutes-vk-singh-slams-media-for-ignoring-good-work/|accessdate=2015-04-20|publisher=Indian Express|date=19 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Singh became Minister of State for [[Ministry of Road Transport and Highways|Road Transport and Highways]].<ref>{{citation |title=PM Modi allocates portfolios. Full list of new ministers |url=https://www.livemint.com/politics/news/pm-modi-allocates-portfolios-full-list-of-new-ministers-1559288502067.html |work=[[Live Mint]] |date=31 May 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Honours and awards==\n===Military awards===\n<center>\n{|\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Param Vishisht Seva Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Ati Vishisht Seva Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Yudh Seva Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=IND Poorvi Star Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=IND Special Service Medal Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=IND Sangram Medal Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=IND Operation Vijay medal.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=IND Operation Parakram medal.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=IND Sainya Seva Medal Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=IND High Altitude Medal Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=IND Videsh Seva Medal Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=IND 50th Anniversary Independence medal.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=IND 25th Anniversary Independence medal.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=IND 30 Years Long Service Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=IND 20YearsServiceMedalRibbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=IND 9YearsServiceMedalRibbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |<center>[[File:Ranger Tab.svg|106px]]</center>\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|<center>[[Param Vishisht Seva Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Ati Vishist Seva Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Yudh Seva Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|Poorvi Star]]</center>\n|-\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|Special Service Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|Sangram Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|Operation Vijay Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|Operation Parakram Medal]]</center>\n|-\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|Sainya Seva Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|High Altitude Service Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|Videsh Seva Medal]]\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|50th Anniversary of Independence Medal]]</center>\n|-\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|25th Anniversary of Independence Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Long service awards|30 Years Long Service Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Long service awards|20 Years Long Service Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Long service awards|9 Years Long Service Medal]]</center>\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |<center>[[Ranger Tab|US Army Ranger Tab]]</center>\n|}</center>\n\nV. K. Singh won the following awards during his career:<ref name=\"Gen. V.K. Singh is new Chief of the Army Staff\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article347272.ece|accessdate=2012-03-26|work=The Hindu|date=1 April 2010 |title=Gen. V.K. Singh is new Chief of the Army Staff}}</ref>\n\n*[[Param Vishisht Seva Medal]]\n*[[Ati Vishisht Seva Medal]]\n*[[Yudh Seva Medal]] for his distinguished service during [[Operation Pawan]]\n\nDuring his service as the COAS, V. K. Singh was appointed Honorary Aide-De-Camp to the [[President of India]]. He was the Colonel of The Rajput Regiment to which he belonged and also Honorary Colonel of The Brigade of Guards, by virtue of being the Army Chief.\n\nOn 11 March 2011, Singh was inducted into the United States Army War College (Class of 2001 graduate) [[United States Army War College International Fellows Hall of Fame|International Fellows Hall of Fame]]. He is the 33rd International Fellow and the first Indian Armed Forces officer to be inducted.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://daily.bhaskar.com/article/NAT-TOP-vk-singh-the-veteran-of-wars-who-lost-the-age-battle-2846615.html?LHS- |title=V. K. Singh: the veteran of wars who lost the age battle|accessdate=2012-03-26|work=Daily Bhaskar|date=26 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Dates of rank==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"background:white\"\n! Insignia !! Rank !! Component !! Date of rank\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |[[File:2nd_Lieutenant_Indian_Army.gif|35px]] || [[Second Lieutenant]] || [[Indian Army]]  || 14 June 1970<ref name=\"commission\">{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=1209  |date=16 October 1971 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |[[File:Lieutenant_of_the_Indian_Army.svg|35px]] || [[Lieutenant]] || [[Indian Army]]  || 14 June 1972<ref>{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=1313  |date=9 September 1972 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |[[File:Captain_of_the_Indian_Army.svg|35px]] || [[Captain (armed forces)|Captain]] || [[Indian Army]] || 14 June 1976<ref>{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=1662  |date=4 December 1976 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |[[File:Major_of_the_Indian_Army.svg|35px]] || [[Major]] || [[Indian Army]] || 14 June 1983\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |[[File:Lieutenant_Colonel_of_the_Indian_Army.svg|35px]] || [[Lieutenant-Colonel]] || [[Indian Army]] || 1 November 1991<ref>{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=379  |date=6 March 1993 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |[[File:Colonel_of_the_Indian_Army.svg|35px]] || [[Colonel]] || [[Indian Army]] || 1 February 1993<ref>{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=939  |date=14 May 1994 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |[[File:Brigadier_of_the_Indian_Army.svg|35px]]  || [[Brigadier]] || [[Indian Army]] || 4 June 1999<ref>{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=20  |date=3 January 2004 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |[[File:Major_General_of_the_Indian_Army.svg|35px]] || [[Major general#India|Major General]] || [[Indian Army]] || 29 June 2004<ref>{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=1208  |date=2 September 2006 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref> \n|-\n|align=\"center\" |[[File:Lieutenant_General_of_the_Indian_Army.svg|35px]]  || [[Lieutenant-General]] || [[Indian Army]] || 1 October 2006<ref>{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=567  |date=7 April 2007 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |[[File:General_of_the_Indian_Army.svg|35px]]  || [[General (India)|General]]<br />(COAS) || [[Indian Army]] || 1 April 2010<ref>{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=1492  |date=28 August 2010 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[[Chief of the Army Staff (India)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://indianarmy.nic.in/Site/FormTemplete/frmTemp1PTC2C.aspx?MnId=gu2SQjjzA2ZrATPYjNNihA==&ParentID=gIyq+7+0NXWW0Oxns3FqNQ==&flag=j4/KYJcjKMntc2WI61dzcw== General V. K. Singh, PVSM, AVSM, YSM, ADC] in the Indian Army official website\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Deepak Kapoor]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[Chief of Army Staff of the Indian Army|Chief of Army Staff]] |years = 31 March 2010\u201331 May 2012}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Bikram Singh (soldier)|Bikram Singh]]}}\n{{succession box\n|before = [[K S Jamwal]]\n|title = [[General_officer_commanding#Usage_in_the_Indian_Army|General Officer-Commanding-in-Chief]] [[Eastern Command (India)|Eastern Command]]\n|years = 1 March 2008 - 31 March 2010\n|after =[[Bikram Singh (general)|Bikram Singh]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[General Officer Commanding]] [[II Corps (India)|II Corps]]|years=-}}\n{{s-aft|after=}}\n|-\n{{s-par|in-lwr}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rajnath Singh]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br />for [[Ghaziabad (Lok Sabha constituency)|Ghaziabad]] |years=2014 \u2013 Present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Paban Singh Ghatowar]]<br/>''Minister of State<br/> with Independent Charge''}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Development of North Eastern Region|Minister of Development of <br>North Eastern Region]]|years=26 May 2014 \u2013 9 November 2014<br/>''Minister of State<br/> with Independent Charge''}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jitendra Singh (politician, born 1956)|Jitendra Singh]]<br/>''Minister of State<br/> with Independent Charge''}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rao Inderjit Singh]]<br/>''(Minister of State with<br/>Independent charge)''}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Statistics and Programme Implementation|Minister of Statistics and Programme Implementation]]<br/>''(Minister of State with<br/>Independent charge)''|years=10 November 2014 \u2013 5 July 2016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[D. V. Sadananda Gowda]]}}\n|-\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Second Narendra Modi Cabinet}}\n{{Cabinet of Narendra Modi}}\n{{16th LS members from Uttar Pradesh}}\n{{Bharatiya Janata Party}}\n{{Chief of the Army Staff India}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Singh, V. K.}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chiefs of Army Staff (India)]]\n[[Category:Indian generals]]\n[[Category:United States Army War College alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Param Vishisht Seva Medal]]\n[[Category:People from Bhiwani district]]\n[[Category:16th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:Lok Sabha members from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Bharatiya Janata Party politicians from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Narendra Modi ministry]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Ghaziabad]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Cadet Corps (India)]]\n[[Category:17th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:National Democratic Alliance candidates in the 2019 Indian general election]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian politician and former army general}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = '''[[The Honourable]]''' <br> [[General (India)|General]]\n| honorific-suffix = [[Param Vishisht Seva Medal|PVSM]], [[Ati Vishisht Seva Medal|AVSM]], [[Yudh Seva Medal|YSM]], [[Aide-de-camp|ADC]], [[Member of parliament, Lok Sabha|MP]]\n| image = [[File:General Vijay Kumar Singh.jpg|200px]]\n| alt = V K Singh\n| office = [[Ministry of Road Transport and Highways|Minister of State for Road Transport and Highways]]\n| primeminister = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| term_start = 30 May 2019\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Mansukh L. Mandaviya]]\n| successor = \n| office1 = [[Minister of External Affairs (India)|Minister of State for External Affairs]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Deepak Kapoor]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| successor1 = [[V. Muraleedharan]]\n| office3 = [[Ministry of Statistics and Programme Implementation|Minister of State (Independent Charge) for Statistics and Programme Implementation]]\n| predecessor3 = [[Rao Inderjit Singh]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| successor3 = [[D. V. Sadananda Gowda]]\n| party = [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n| office2 = [[Ministry of Development of North Eastern Region|Minister of State (Independent Charge) for Development of the North Eastern Region]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Paban Singh Ghatowar]]\n| successor2 = [[Jitendra Singh (BJP politician)|Jitendra Singh]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1951|5|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Bhiwani]], [[East Punjab|Punjab]], [[India]]<br />(now in [[Haryana]], [[India]])\n| nationality = [[Indian People|Indian]]\n| alma_mater = [[National Defence Academy (India)]]<br />[[Indian Military Academy]]<br />[[Defence Services Staff College]]<br />[[United States Army War College]]\n| term_start1 = 26 May 2014\n| term_end1 = 30 May 2019\n| term_start2 = 26 May 2014\n| term_end2 = 9 November 2014\n| term_start3 = 9 November 2014\n| term_end3 = 5 July 2016\n| office4 = [[Lok Sabha|Member of Parliament, Lok Sabha]]\n| term_start4 = 16 May 2014\n| term_end4 = \n| constituency4 = [[Ghaziabad (Lok Sabha constituency)|Ghaziabad]]\n| predecessor4 = [[Rajnath Singh]]\n| majority4 = 501,500 (61.96%)\n| successor4 = Incumbent\n| office5 = 24th [[Chief of Army Staff (India)|Chief of the Army Staff]]\n| president5 = [[Pratibha Patil]]\n| primeminister5 = [[Manmohan Singh]]\n| term_start5 = 31 March 2010\n| term_end5 = 31 May 2012\n| predecessor5 = [[Deepak Kapoor]]\n| successor5 = [[Bikram Singh (general)|Bikram Singh]]\n| nickname = \n| allegiance = {{flag|India}}\n| branch = {{army|India}}\n| serviceyears = 14 June 1970 - 31 May 2012\n| rank = [[File:General of the Indian Army.svg|20px]] [[General (India)|General]]\n| servicenumber = IC-24173<ref name=\"commission\"/>\n| unit = [[Rajput Regiment]]\n| commands = [[Chief of the Army Staff (India)| Chief of Army Staff]] <br />[[Eastern Command (India)|Eastern Army]]<br />[[II Corps (India)|II Corps]]<br />Victor Force, [[Rashtriya Rifles]]<br/>168th Infantry Brigade<br/> 2nd Btn. [[Rajput Regiment]] (Kali Chindi)\n| battles = [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971]]<br/>[[Operation Pawan]]<br/>[[Kargil War]]\n| awards = [[File:Param Vishisht Seva Medal ribbon.svg|33px]] [[Param Vishisht Seva Medal]]<br/>[[File:Ati Vishisht Seva Medal ribbon.svg|33px]] [[Ati Vishisht Seva Medal]]<br />[[File:Yudh Seva Medal ribbon.svg|33px]] [[Yudh Seva Medal]]<br />[[File:Ranger Tab.svg|33px]] [[Ranger Tab]]\n}}\n\n[[General (India)|General]] '''Vijay Kumar Singh''', {{small|[[Param Vishisht Seva Medal|PVSM]], [[Ati Vishisht Seva Medal|AVSM]], [[Yudh Seva Medal|YSM]], [[Aide-de-camp|ADC]], [[Member of parliament, Lok Sabha|MP]]}} (born 10 May 1951) is an Indian politician and a retired [[Four-star rank|four-star]] General in the [[Indian Army]]. Since May 30, 2019, he is serving as the [[Minister of State]] for [[Ministry of Road Transport and Highways|Road Transport and Highways]] in the [[Second Modi ministry]]. He previously served as [[Minister of State]] for [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|External Affairs]] in the [[First Modi ministry]] and as [[Minister of State (Independent Charge)]] for [[Northeast India|Development of the North-Eastern Region]].\n\nDuring his military career, Singh served as the 23rd [[Chief of Army Staff (India)|Chief of the Army Staff]] from 2010 to 2012. Singh took the  [[Government of India]] to court in a dispute over his date of birth and subsequent retirement, becoming the first serving Indian [[Chief of the Army Staff (India)|military Chief of Staff]] to take legal action against the Indian government.\n\nAfter his retirement from the military, Singh joined the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) in 2014 and was elected [[Member of Parliament (India)|Member of Parliament]] of the [[Lok Sabha]] for the [[Ghaziabad (Lok Sabha constituency)|Ghaziabad constituency]] of [[Uttar Pradesh]]\nin [[2014 Indian general election|that year's general election]]. He was re-elected to the same seat in [[2019 Indian general election|2019]].\n\nSingh has written an autobiography called ''[[Courage and Conviction]]''.\n\n==Early life and education==\nGen Vijay Kumar Singh was born in [[Bapora]] village in the state [[Haryana]]. His father was a Colonel in the Indian Army and grandfather a [[Junior Commissioned Officer]]. Singh was educated at [[Birla Public School]] in [[Pilani]], [[Rajasthan]]. He is an alumnus of [[National Defence Academy (India)|National Defence Academy]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20100124/main6.htm|title=Bapoda village basks in Gen VK Singh\u2019s glory|last=Mohan|first=Raman|date=24 January 2010|publisher=The Tribune |accessdate=2010-04-03 |location=Chandigarh}}</ref>\n\n==Military career==\nSingh was commissioned into the 2nd Battalion of the [[Rajput Regiment]] (Kali Chindi) on 14 June 1970.<ref name=\"commission\"/> He commanded the same unit when it was positioned along the [[Line of Control]] with Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dutta|first=Sujan|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1110730/jsp/nation/story_14309462.jsp |title=Generation shift in air force |date=30 July 2011 |work=The Telegraph |accessdate=2012-03-26}}</ref>\n\nHe graduated from the [[Defence Services Staff College]]. He was an honours graduate of the [[United States Army Infantry School]], a graduate of the [[Ranger School|Rangers Course]] at [[Fort Benning]] and the [[United States Army War College]] in [[Carlisle, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=DNA20100331>{{cite news |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report_gen-vk-singh-battles-odds-becomes-26th-army-chief_1365552 |title=Gen VK Singh battles odds, becomes 26th army chief |publisher=DNA |date=31 March 2010 |accessdate=2012-03-26}}</ref>\n\nSingh is experienced in both [[counter-insurgency]] and [[Mountain warfare|high-altitude]] operations. He also saw action as a young [[Lieutenant]] in the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971]] while serving as an intelligence officer of 2 [[Rajput Regiment|Rajput]].{{citation needed|date=April 2015}} During his career he has served in various positions:\n* Instructor in the [[Indian Military Training Team]] (IMTRAT) headquarters in [[Bhutan]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Courage and conviction : an autobiography |isbn=9789382277576 |page=122}}</ref>\n* Instructor at [[Army War College, Mhow|Infantry School]] twice and Chief Instructor at JLW (Commando Wing), [[Belgaum#Defence training centres|Belgaum]].<ref name=saisam10>{{cite news|title=Change of Guard - General VK Singh new COAS|url=http://sainiksamachar.nic.in/englisharchives/2010/apr16-10/h1.htm|accessdate=2014-06-15|publisher=Sainik Samachar|date=10 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Did you know: Gen VK Singh is a small time movie star!|url=http://www.firstpost.com/india/did-you-know-gen-vk-singh-is-a-small-time-movie-star-190673.html|accessdate=2014-06-15|publisher=First Post|date=23 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=When the army chief did a cameo in Bollywood|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/When+the+army+chief+did+a+cameo+in+Bollywood/1/91040.html|accessdate=2014-06-15|publisher=India Today|date=3 April 2010}}</ref>\n* Military Operations Directorate at the Army Headquarters.\n*Served as [[Commanding Officer|CO]] 2 Rajput, the battalion he was commissioned in.\n*Served as the Colonel General Staff (Col GS) of 12 Infantry Division\n*Commanded the 168 Infantry brigade at [[Samba, Jammu|Samba]].<ref name=saisam10/><ref name=is10>{{cite news|title=Gen V K Singh takes over as Army Chief|url=http://www.indiastrategic.in/topstories556.htm|accessdate=2014-06-15|publisher=India Strategic|date=31 March 2010}}</ref>\n* Brigadier General Staff (BGS) of [[Jalandhar]] based [[XI Corps (India)|XI Corps]] during [[Operation Parakram]] when Indian troops were mobilised on the border in the wake of the attack on the Indian Parliament in 2001.\n* Commanded the Victor Force, part of the [[Rashtriya Rifles]].\n* Commanded [[Ambala]]-based [[II Corps (India)|II Corps]].\n* Commanded the Army's [[Eastern Command (India)|Eastern Command]].\n\nSingh became the 24th Chief of Army Staff on 31 March 2010, and was the first commando to achieve that position.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiastrategic.in/topstories556.htm|title=Gen V K Singh takes over as Army Chief|date=March 2010|website=India Strategic|accessdate=2014-05-27}}</ref> Towards the end of his career there was a dispute regarding his date of birth, causing him to become the first serving officer of the Indian Army to take the government to court.<ref name=NDTV20120326>{{cite news|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/army-chief-discloses-offer-of-rs-14-crore-bribe-cbi-inquiry-ordered-189957|accessdate=2012-03-26 |title=Details of who allegedly offered Rs. 14-crore bribe to Army chief |first=Nitin A.|last=Gokhale|work=NDTV|date=26 March 2012}}</ref> As a consequence of an error made when he had enrolled with the [[National Defence Academy]] in 1965, official records misstated the year in which he was born. He withdrew the writ in February 2012 when, according to ''[[The Hindu]]'', the [[Supreme Court of India]] \"refused to intervene\". The Court noted that there was no dispute regarding his actual date of birth and that the matter being contested was regarding how that had been recorded. It ruled that Singh had on three occasions accepted the misrecorded date.<ref name=\"The Hindu 20120210\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article2878671.ece |title=Army Chief loses age war |publisher=The Hindu|date=10 February 2012|accessdate=2012-02-11 |first=J. |last=Venkatesan}}</ref>\n\nThe [[BBC]] noted in 2012 that defence experts considered a drive to modernise the Indian army had suffered from \"a lack of planning and acrimony between the military and the defence ministry\". This report followed an interview given by Singh in March 2012 that had caused a political row. Singh said that over a year earlier he had reported to [[A. K. Antony]], the defence minister, that he had been offered a bribe of {{USD}}2.7 million if the army bought several hundred sub-standard vehicles. Antony issued a rebuttal to the interview, saying that he had requested at the time that Singh provide a written report regarding the incident and that this had never been submitted. Two days after the interview with Singh, correspondence between the general and the [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]], [[Manmohan Singh]], was leaked. This criticised the standard of India's defences and caused a further political row.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-12769214 |title=India's corruption scandals |publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\nSingh retired as Chief of Army Staff on 31 May 2012. He was succeeded by General [[Bikram Singh (soldier)|Bikram Singh]].<ref>{{cite news| url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article3474071.ece |title = Gen. V.K. Singh to retire today|work==The Hindu|date=31 May 2012 |accessdate=2012-05-31}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nSubsequent to his retirement from the military, Singh showed support for the [[2012 Indian anti-corruption movement|anti-corruption movement]].<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article3723926.ece|title=V.K. Singh: throw the corrupt out of power |date= 4 August 2012}}</ref> He was seen on the stage in August 2012 at the [[Ramlila Maidan]] in [[New Delhi]], where [[Ramdev]] was fasting in protest of alleged black money and corruption. He was reported to have declared that \"It is shocking but true that over two lakh farmers have committed suicide since 1995. The problems of farmers will have to take the forefront in this movement as the government has turned a blind eye to their woes.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Mohammad |last=Ali |title=Ramdev takes on Congress, warns of march to Parliament |work=The Hindu |date=13 August 2014 |url =http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/ramdev-takes-on-congress-warns-of-march-to-parliament/article3757648.ece}}</ref> Around that time he also compared the movement, whose principal figurehead was [[Anna Hazare]], to that of the [[Bihar Movement]] that had been led by [[Jayaprakash Narayan]] in 1975. He said that \"When I evaluate the country's present condition, it is similar to that of 1975. Jayaprakash Narayan had then said ''Vacate the throne, common people are coming''. He felt then that corruption is the root of all problems&nbsp;... the situation in the country is the same today\".<ref>{{cite news |agency=ANI |title =VK Singh now battles with Baba Ramdev |work=Zee News |date=12 August 2012|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/nation/vk-singh-now-battles-with-baba-ramdev_793178.html}}</ref>\n\n[[File:GNLU VC with VK Singh.jpg|thumb|right|250px|V.K Singh at an International conference at the Center for Foreign Policy and Security Studies, [[Gujarat National Law University]]]]\nSingh led an agitation with Yoga Guru [[Ramdev]] on 23 December 2012, at [[Jantar Mantar]], New Delhi, on the [[2012 Delhi gang rape case]]<ref>{{cite news |agency=PTI |title=V K Singh, Baba Ramdev named in FIR for violence at Jantar Mantar |work=Financial Express |date =24 December 2012 |url=http://www.financialexpress.com/news/v-k-singh-baba-ramdev-named-in-fir-for-violence-at-jantar-mantar/1049641}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=V K Singh, Ramdev named in FIR for violence at Jantar Mantar |work=Times of India|date=24 December 2012 |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/videos/news/V-K-Singh-Ramdev-named-in-FIR-for-violence-at-Jantar-Mantar/videoshow/17745058.cms }}</ref>\n\nSingh joined the Bharatiya Janata Party on 1 March 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Former Army Chief Gen. V K Singh joins BJP along with other Officers |url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/03/former-army-chief-gen-v-k-singh-joins-bjp-along-with-other-officers/ |agency=IANS |date=1 March 2014 |work=Bihar Prabha |accessdate=2014-03-01}}</ref> He won the [[Ghaziabad (Lok Sabha constituency)]] seat in the 2014 Indian general election, defeating [[Raj Babbar]] of the [[Indian National Congress]] by a margin of 567,260 votes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sinha |first1=Arunav |title=Former chief of Army staff General (retired) VK Singh defeats Raj Babbar of Congress by 567260 votes to register a win at Ghaziabad. |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/Former-chief-of-Army-staff-General-retired-VK-Singh-defeats-Raj-Babbar-of-Congress-by-567260-votes-to-register-a-win-at-Ghaziabad-/articleshow/35217329.cms? |accessdate=15 January 2017 |work=The Times of India |agency=TNN |date=16 May 2014 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170115204357/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/Former-chief-of-Army-staff-General-retired-VK-Singh-defeats-Raj-Babbar-of-Congress-by-567260-votes-to-register-a-win-at-Ghaziabad-/articleshow/35217329.cms? |archivedate=15 January 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He was re-elected in a landslide during the [[2019 Indian general election]].\n\n===Union minister===\nIn May 2014, Singh was appointed as Minister of State of External Affairs and Minister of state (independent charge) for North East Region in the NDA-led Indian Government.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/list-of-ministers-in-narendra-modis-government/articleshow/35626035.cms |title=List of ministers in Narendra Modi's government |work=Economic Times |date=27 May 2014 |accessdate=2014-06-07}}</ref> He was relieved of responsibility for the North East Region in November 2014, when Jitendra Singh replaced him.<ref>{{cite news |title=What went wrong? VK Singh lost Doner to MoS for personnel Jitendra Singh |first=Aman |last=Sharma |date=11 November 2014 |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/what-went-wrong-vk-singh-lost-doner-to-mos-for-personnel-jitendra-singh/articleshow/45104244.cms |work=Economic Times |accessdate=2015-04-21}}</ref> He has held the office of Minister of State (Independent Charge) under the Statistics and Programme Implementation portfolio in the NDA government.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nSingh is praised for leading [[Operation Raahat]], a rescue mission to evacuate Indian citizens and other foreign nationals from [[Yemen]] during 2015 [[Yemeni Crisis (2011\u2013present)|Yemeni Crisis]].<ref name=hindu-evac>{{cite news|title=India begins evacuating citizens|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/india-begins-evacuating-citizens/article7054994.ece|publisher=The Hindu|date=31 March 2015|accessdate=2015-03-31}}</ref> Prime Minister Narendra Modi in April 2015 said, \u201cI believe this is the first time in the world that a government minister has stood on the battlefield like a soldier to do this work&nbsp;... I salute General V. K. Singh.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|title=Presstitutes remark row: PM Narendra Modi says media ignoring V K Singh\u2019s good work in Yemen|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/pm-salutes-vk-singh-slams-media-for-ignoring-good-work/|accessdate=2015-04-20|publisher=Indian Express|date=19 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Singh became Minister of State for [[Ministry of Road Transport and Highways|Road Transport and Highways]].<ref>{{citation |title=PM Modi allocates portfolios. Full list of new ministers |url=https://www.livemint.com/politics/news/pm-modi-allocates-portfolios-full-list-of-new-ministers-1559288502067.html |work=[[Live Mint]] |date=31 May 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Honours and awards==\n===Military awards===\n<center>\n{|\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Param Vishisht Seva Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Ati Vishisht Seva Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Yudh Seva Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=IND Poorvi Star Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=IND Special Service Medal Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=IND Sangram Medal Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=IND Operation Vijay medal.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=IND Operation Parakram medal.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=IND Sainya Seva Medal Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=IND High Altitude Medal Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=IND Videsh Seva Medal Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=IND 50th Anniversary Independence medal.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=IND 25th Anniversary Independence medal.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=IND 30 Years Long Service Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=IND 20YearsServiceMedalRibbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=IND 9YearsServiceMedalRibbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |<center>[[File:Ranger Tab.svg|106px]]</center>\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|<center>[[Param Vishisht Seva Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Ati Vishist Seva Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Yudh Seva Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|Poorvi Star]]</center>\n|-\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|Special Service Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|Sangram Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|Operation Vijay Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|Operation Parakram Medal]]</center>\n|-\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|Sainya Seva Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|High Altitude Service Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|Videsh Seva Medal]]\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|50th Anniversary of Independence Medal]]</center>\n|-\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|25th Anniversary of Independence Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Long service awards|30 Years Long Service Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Long service awards|20 Years Long Service Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Long service awards|9 Years Long Service Medal]]</center>\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |<center>[[Ranger Tab|US Army Ranger Tab]]</center>\n|}</center>\n\nV. K. Singh won the following awards during his career:<ref name=\"Gen. V.K. Singh is new Chief of the Army Staff\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article347272.ece|accessdate=2012-03-26|work=The Hindu|date=1 April 2010 |title=Gen. V.K. Singh is new Chief of the Army Staff}}</ref>\n\n*[[Param Vishisht Seva Medal]]\n*[[Ati Vishisht Seva Medal]]\n*[[Yudh Seva Medal]] for his distinguished service during [[Operation Pawan]]\n\nDuring his service as the COAS, V. K. Singh was appointed Honorary Aide-De-Camp to the [[President of India]]. He was the Colonel of The Rajput Regiment to which he belonged and also Honorary Colonel of The Brigade of Guards, by virtue of being the Army Chief.\n\nOn 11 March 2011, Singh was inducted into the United States Army War College (Class of 2001 graduate) [[United States Army War College International Fellows Hall of Fame|International Fellows Hall of Fame]]. He is the 33rd International Fellow and the first Indian Armed Forces officer to be inducted.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://daily.bhaskar.com/article/NAT-TOP-vk-singh-the-veteran-of-wars-who-lost-the-age-battle-2846615.html?LHS- |title=V. K. Singh: the veteran of wars who lost the age battle|accessdate=2012-03-26|work=Daily Bhaskar|date=26 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Dates of rank==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"background:white\"\n! Insignia !! Rank !! Component !! Date of rank\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |[[File:2nd_Lieutenant_Indian_Army.gif|35px]] || [[Second Lieutenant]] || [[Indian Army]]  || 14 June 1970<ref name=\"commission\">{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=1209  |date=16 October 1971 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |[[File:Lieutenant_of_the_Indian_Army.svg|35px]] || [[Lieutenant]] || [[Indian Army]]  || 14 June 1972<ref>{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=1313  |date=9 September 1972 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |[[File:Captain_of_the_Indian_Army.svg|35px]] || [[Captain (armed forces)|Captain]] || [[Indian Army]] || 14 June 1976<ref>{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=1662  |date=4 December 1976 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |[[File:Major_of_the_Indian_Army.svg|35px]] || [[Major]] || [[Indian Army]] || 14 June 1983\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |[[File:Lieutenant_Colonel_of_the_Indian_Army.svg|35px]] || [[Lieutenant-Colonel]] || [[Indian Army]] || 1 November 1991<ref>{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=379  |date=6 March 1993 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |[[File:Colonel_of_the_Indian_Army.svg|35px]] || [[Colonel]] || [[Indian Army]] || 1 February 1993<ref>{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=939  |date=14 May 1994 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |[[File:Brigadier_of_the_Indian_Army.svg|35px]]  || [[Brigadier]] || [[Indian Army]] || 4 June 1999<ref>{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=20  |date=3 January 2004 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |[[File:Major_General_of_the_Indian_Army.svg|35px]] || [[Major general#India|Major General]] || [[Indian Army]] || 29 June 2004<ref>{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=1208  |date=2 September 2006 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref> \n|-\n|align=\"center\" |[[File:Lieutenant_General_of_the_Indian_Army.svg|35px]]  || [[Lieutenant-General]] || [[Indian Army]] || 1 October 2006<ref>{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=567  |date=7 April 2007 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |[[File:General_of_the_Indian_Army.svg|35px]]  || [[General (India)|General]]<br />(COAS) || [[Indian Army]] || 1 April 2010<ref>{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=1492  |date=28 August 2010 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[[Chief of the Army Staff (India)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://indianarmy.nic.in/Site/FormTemplete/frmTemp1PTC2C.aspx?MnId=gu2SQjjzA2ZrATPYjNNihA==&ParentID=gIyq+7+0NXWW0Oxns3FqNQ==&flag=j4/KYJcjKMntc2WI61dzcw== General V. K. Singh, PVSM, AVSM, YSM, ADC] in the Indian Army official website\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Deepak Kapoor]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[Chief of Army Staff of the Indian Army|Chief of Army Staff]] |years = 31 March 2010\u201331 May 2012}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Bikram Singh (soldier)|Bikram Singh]]}}\n{{succession box\n|before = [[K S Jamwal]]\n|title = [[General_officer_commanding#Usage_in_the_Indian_Army|General Officer-Commanding-in-Chief]] [[Eastern Command (India)|Eastern Command]]\n|years = 1 March 2008 - 31 March 2010\n|after =[[Bikram Singh (general)|Bikram Singh]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[General Officer Commanding]] [[II Corps (India)|II Corps]]|years=-}}\n{{s-aft|after=}}\n|-\n{{s-par|in-lwr}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rajnath Singh]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br />for [[Ghaziabad (Lok Sabha constituency)|Ghaziabad]] |years=2014 \u2013 Present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Paban Singh Ghatowar]]<br/>''Minister of State<br/> with Independent Charge''}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Development of North Eastern Region|Minister of Development of <br>North Eastern Region]]|years=26 May 2014 \u2013 9 November 2014<br/>''Minister of State<br/> with Independent Charge''}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jitendra Singh (politician, born 1956)|Jitendra Singh]]<br/>''Minister of State<br/> with Independent Charge''}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rao Inderjit Singh]]<br/>''(Minister of State with<br/>Independent charge)''}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Statistics and Programme Implementation|Minister of Statistics and Programme Implementation]]<br/>''(Minister of State with<br/>Independent charge)''|years=10 November 2014 \u2013 5 July 2016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[D. V. Sadananda Gowda]]}}\n|-\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Second Narendra Modi Cabinet}}\n{{Cabinet of Narendra Modi}}\n{{16th LS members from Uttar Pradesh}}\n{{Bharatiya Janata Party}}\n{{Chief of the Army Staff India}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Singh, V. K.}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chiefs of Army Staff (India)]]\n[[Category:Indian generals]]\n[[Category:United States Army War College alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Param Vishisht Seva Medal]]\n[[Category:People from Bhiwani district]]\n[[Category:16th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:Lok Sabha members from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Bharatiya Janata Party politicians from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Narendra Modi ministry]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Ghaziabad]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Cadet Corps (India)]]\n[[Category:17th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:National Democratic Alliance candidates in the 2019 Indian general election]]\n", "name_user": "Baffle gab1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life and education", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/V._K._Singh"}
{"title_page": "Alfred William Begbie", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2019}}\n{{short description|British civil servant in India}}\n'''Alfred William Begbie''' was a [[British people|British]] [[Civil Service|civil servant]] in [[India]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=O94NAAAAQAAJ&printsec=titlepage&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0 The Bengal directory and annual register #41]</ref>\n\nHe got nominated to [[East India Company College]],<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=x_8nAAAAYAAJ&printsec=toc&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0 East-India Register and Directory #xxxvii]</ref> 14 January 1818.\n\nBegbie passed ''the Public Examination'' with great credit from [[East India Company College|College at Haileybury]] in [[Hertfordshire]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=OPbiZPTdVUAC&printsec=titlepage&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0 The Asiatic journal and monthly miscellany By East India Company #105]</ref> on 28 May 1818.\n\nHe was awarded prize in [[Bengali language|Bengali]] and great credit in other departments in the ''Public Examination'' at [[East India Company College]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=WiAYAAAAYAAJ&printsec=titlepage&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0 The Asiatic journal and monthly register for British and foreign India #57]</ref> on 3 December 1819.\n\nBegbie was appointed as Assistant to Magistrate of Northern Division of [[Bundelkhand|Bundelcund]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=0qgIAAAAQAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0 The Asiatic journal and monthly register for British India and its dependencies #374]</ref> on 16 February 1821.\n\nOn 10 August 1822 Begbie was appointed as Register of Civil Court of Northern Division of Bundelcund.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=zXiILz2MABEC&printsec=titlepage&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0 The Asiatic journal and monthly miscellany #175]</ref>\n\nHe married Margaret Anna (daughter of James Grant) at [[Allahabad]] on 30 August 1825.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ts2HWYMKmUwC&printsec=titlepage&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0 The Asiatic journal and monthly miscellany By East India Company #287]</ref> Frances Charlotte was their daughter.<ref>[http://thepeerage.com/p20137.htm#i201364 thePeerage.com A genealogical survey of the peerage of Britain as well as the royal families of Europe]</ref>\n\nBegbie 26 November 1825 Begbie was appointed Deputy Collector of [[Banda district (India)|Banda]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ts2HWYMKmUwC&printsec=titlepage&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0 The Asiatic journal and monthly miscellany By East India Company #715]</ref>\n\nHis wife died at [[Hamirpur, Himachal Pradesh|Humeerpore]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=hygi657h5UIC&printsec=titlepage&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0 The Asiatic journal and monthly miscellany By East India Company #266]</ref> on 23 June 1828.\n\nBegbie remarried Margaret Watt (eldest daughter of the Isaac Watt, Esq., of Logie, Angusshire, Scotland) at Allahabad on 22 February 1836.<ref>[http://www.search.fibis.org/frontis/bin/aps_detail.php?id=120291&FrontisID=6ff72359d90e95d6a04406735cf64c16 FIBIS: Marriage announcements taken from the East India Register]{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Gertrude Emma (born 7 February 1842) was their daughter.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/visitationofengl06howa/visitationofengl06howa_djvu.txt Full text of \"Visitation of England and Wales\"]</ref>\n\nOn 2 June 1837 he was appointed as Civil & Session Judge of Mynpoorie by [[List of Lieutenant Governors of the North-Western Provinces|lieutenant Governors of the North-Western Provinces]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=WS8oAAAAYAAJ&printsec=titlepage&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0 The Asiatic Journal and Monthly Miscellany By East India Company #230]</ref>\n\nDuring January to June 1853 (at least) he was Judge at the [[Sadr Nizamat Adalat|Niz\u0101mat \u02bfAd\u0101lat]] of [[North-Western Provinces]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=FvASAAAAYAAJ&printsec=titlepage&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0 Decisions of the Nizamut Adawlut By North-Western Provinces, India]</ref>\n\nFrom 10 October 1853 to 7 November 1853 he held position of [[List of Lieutenant Governors of the North-Western Provinces|Lieutenant-Governor]] of the [[North-Western Provinces]] as an ''In charge (acting)''.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=3VQTAAAAYAAJ&printsec=toc&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0 The India List and India Office List By India Office, Great Britain #130]</ref>\n\n'''Personal Life'''\n \nAlfred William Begbie was born in 1801 at Hendon, Middlesex England. His parents were Peter Begbie & Frances (Jones) Begbie. \n\nAlfred William Begbie married Margaret Anna Grant  at Allahabad on 30 August 1825.  <ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:FGNC-84K \"India Marriages, 1792-1948 ,\" database, FamilySearch] Alfred William Begbie and Margaret Anna Grant, 30 Aug 1824; citing Allahabad, Bengal, India, reference ; FHL microfilm 498,981</ref>\n\nAlfred and Margaret had two daughters,  Frances Charlotte Begbie born in 1825 <ref> [https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:FG6M-26J \"India Births and Baptisms, 1786-1947,\" database, FamilySearch] Frances Charlotte Begbee, 21 Oct 1825; citing , reference ; FHL microfilm 498,955.</ref> and Emelia Georgeana Begbie born in 1826. <ref> [https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:FGDX-SGS \"India Births and Baptisms, 1786-1947,\" database, FamilySearch] Emelia Georgeana Bigbee, 20 Jan 1827; citing , reference ; FHL microfilm 498,957.</ref>\n\nMargaret Anna (Grant) Begbie passed away on 23 June 1828 at Humeerpore, India.  <ref>The Asiatic Journal and Monthly Miscellany, Volume 25; ''At Humpeerpore, the lady of A.W. Begbie Esq., of the civil service''</ref>\n\nAlfred married Charlotte Augusta Ricketts in 1831 at Humeerpore, Bengal, India. <ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:FGFB-NWT \"India Marriages, 1792-1948] ,\" database, FamilySearch: Alfred William Begbie and Charlotte Augusta Ricketts, 09 Jun 1831; citing Humeerpore, Bengal, India, reference ; FHL microfilm 498,964.</ref>\n\nCharlotte Augusta (Ricketts) Begbie passed away in 1833 at Zillah, Bengal, India. <ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:FGL7-FNY \"India Deaths and Burials, 1719-1948,\" database, FamilySearch] Charlotte Augusta Begbie, 22 Aug 1833; citing ; FHL microfilm 498,969.</ref>\n\nAlfred William Begbie married Margaret Watt (eldest daughter of the Isaac Watt, Esq., of Logie, Angusshire, Scotland) at Allahabad on 22 February 1836. <ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:FGN4-9X2 \"India Marriages, 1792-1948 ,\" database, FamilySearch]  :Alfred William Begbie and Margaret Watt, 22 Feb 1836; citing Allahabad, Bengal, India, reference ; FHL microfilm 498,973.</ref>\n\nAlfred and Margaret (Watt) Begbie had one daughter, Gertrude Emma Begbie who was born 20 February 1842. <ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:FG39-629 \"India Births and Baptisms, 1786-1947,\" database, FamilySearch] Gertrude Emma Begbie, 11 Mar 1842; citing , reference v 63 p 36; FHL microfilm 498,980. </ref>\n\nMargaret (Watt) Begbie passed away  in December 1842 and was buried 14 December 1842 at Landour, Bengal, India. <ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:FGPH-WW1  \"India Deaths and Burials, 1719-1948,\" database, FamilySearch] Begby, 14 Dec 1842; citing ; FHL microfilm 498,980. ''Begby (Female) was buried 14 December 1842 Landour, Bengal, India; Marital Status: Married: Spouse's Name: Begby''</ref>\n\nAlfred William Begbie married Lucy Sharp in 1848 at Simla, Bengal, India. <ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:FGN7-37N \"India Marriages, 1792-1948 ,\" database, FamilySearch] Alfred William Begbie and Lucy Sharp, 14 Oct 1848; citing Simla, Bengal, India, reference ; FHL microfilm 498,986.</ref>\n\nAlfred and Lucy (Sharp) had one son, Alfred John Begbie who was born 21 October 1849 at Chr. Agra, Bengal, India. <ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:FGQQ-8PX  \"India Births and Baptisms, 1786-1947,\" database, FamilySearch] Alfred John Begbie, 11 Jan 1850; citing CHR AGRA BENGAL INDIA, reference ; FHL microfilm 498,988. </ref>\n\nThe England Census of 1861 records: Alfred W Begbie age 59, occupation: Bengal Civil Service Retired, and his wife, Lucy Begbie age 57, and their children: Gertrude Emma Begbie age 19, Alfred John Begbie age 11, and their grandson, Alexander William D Campbell age 12 are living at Lansdowne Calvery Park Gardens, Tonbridge, Kent, England. The household employs three female servants and one male servant. <ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:Q2MP-DGG2 \"England and Wales Census, 1861,\" database with images, FamilySearch]</ref>  \n\nThe England Census of 1871 records: Alfred W Begbie age 69, born Hendon, Middlesex, occupation: Bengal Civil Service, and his wife, Lucy Begbie age 61, born Coventry Warwickshire, and their son Alfred J Begbie age 21, born East Indies, occupation: Undergraduate, are living at Tunbridge Wells, Tunbridge, Kent, England. Visiting them is Frederick A Sarthan age 20, born Manchester, Lancshire, occupation: Undergraduate. The household employs three female and one male servant. <ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:VF62-YXS \"England and Wales Census, 1871\", database with images, FamilySearch]</ref> \n\nAlfred William Begbie age 71,  passed away 05 June 1873 at Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England. <ref>[http://www.freebmd.org.uk/ Free BMD England & Wales BMD Registration Index 1837-2007] BEGBIE Alfred William age 71 died June q. 1873 at Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England (Vol. 2a Page\t298)</ref> He left effects valued at under \u00a314,000. <ref> Probate of Will: [https://probatesearch.service.gov.uk/#wills  Probate Search UK \u2013 Find a Will]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n[[File:PD-icon.svg|15px|link=|alt=]]&nbsp;''The above sources are in the [[public domain]].''\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{succession box \n| title=[[List of Lieutenant Governors of the North-Western Provinces|Lieutenant Governor of the North-Western Provinces]] <br> ''Acting''\n| before=[[James Thomason (British colonial governor)|James Thomason]] \n| after=[[John Russell Colvin|J. R. Colvin]] \n| years=10 October 1853 &ndash; 7 November 1853}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Begbie, A. W.}}\n[[Category:British East India Company civil servants]]\n[[Category:Lieutenant-Governors of the North-Western Provinces]]\n[[Category:1800 births]]\n[[Category:1889 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2019}}\n{{short description|British civil servant in India}}\n'''Alfred William Begbie''' was a [[British people|British]] [[Civil Service|civil servant]] in [[India]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=O94NAAAAQAAJ&printsec=titlepage&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0 The Bengal directory and annual register #41]</ref>\n\nHe got nominated to [[East India Company College]],<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=x_8nAAAAYAAJ&printsec=toc&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0 East-India Register and Directory #xxxvii]</ref> 14 January 1818.\n\nBegbie passed ''the Public Examination'' with great credit from [[East India Company College|College at Haileybury]] in [[Hertfordshire]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=OPbiZPTdVUAC&printsec=titlepage&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0 The Asiatic journal and monthly miscellany By East India Company #105]</ref> on 28 May 1818.\n\nHe was awarded prize in [[Bengali language|Bengali]] and great credit in other departments in the ''Public Examination'' at [[East India Company College]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=WiAYAAAAYAAJ&printsec=titlepage&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0 The Asiatic journal and monthly register for British and foreign India #57]</ref> on 3 December 1819.\n\nBegbie was appointed as Assistant to Magistrate of Northern Division of [[Bundelkhand|Bundelcund]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=0qgIAAAAQAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0 The Asiatic journal and monthly register for British India and its dependencies #374]</ref> on 16 February 1821.\n\nOn 10 August 1822 Begbie was appointed as Register of Civil Court of Northern Division of Bundelcund.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=zXiILz2MABEC&printsec=titlepage&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0 The Asiatic journal and monthly miscellany #175]</ref>\n\nHe married Margaret Anna (daughter of James Grant) at [[Allahabad]] on 30 August 1825.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ts2HWYMKmUwC&printsec=titlepage&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0 The Asiatic journal and monthly miscellany By East India Company #287]</ref> Frances Charlotte was their daughter.<ref>[http://thepeerage.com/p20137.htm#i201364 thePeerage.com A genealogical survey of the peerage of Britain as well as the royal families of Europe]</ref>\n\nBegbie 26 November 1825 Begbie was appointed Deputy Collector of [[Banda district (India)|Banda]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ts2HWYMKmUwC&printsec=titlepage&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0 The Asiatic journal and monthly miscellany By East India Company #715]</ref>\n\nHis wife died at [[Hamirpur, Himachal Pradesh|Humeerpore]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=hygi657h5UIC&printsec=titlepage&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0 The Asiatic journal and monthly miscellany By East India Company #266]</ref> on 23 June 1828.\n\nBegbie remarried Margaret Watt (eldest daughter of the Isaac Watt, Esq., of Logie, Angusshire, Scotland) at Allahabad on 22 February 1836.<ref>[http://www.search.fibis.org/frontis/bin/aps_detail.php?id=120291&FrontisID=6ff72359d90e95d6a04406735cf64c16 FIBIS: Marriage announcements taken from the East India Register]{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Gertrude Emma (born 7 February 1842) was their daughter.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/visitationofengl06howa/visitationofengl06howa_djvu.txt Full text of \"Visitation of England and Wales\"]</ref>\n\nOn 2 June 1837 he was appointed as Civil & Session Judge of Mynpoorie by [[List of Lieutenant Governors of the North-Western Provinces|lieutenant Governors of the North-Western Provinces]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=WS8oAAAAYAAJ&printsec=titlepage&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0 The Asiatic Journal and Monthly Miscellany By East India Company #230]</ref>\n\nDuring January to June 1853 (at least) he was Judge at the [[Sadr Nizamat Adalat|Niz\u0101mat \u02bfAd\u0101lat]] of [[North-Western Provinces]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=FvASAAAAYAAJ&printsec=titlepage&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0 Decisions of the Nizamut Adawlut By North-Western Provinces, India]</ref>\n\nFrom 10 October 1853 to 7 November 1853 he held position of [[List of Lieutenant Governors of the North-Western Provinces|Lieutenant-Governor]] of the [[North-Western Provinces]] as an ''In charge (acting)''.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=3VQTAAAAYAAJ&printsec=toc&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0 The India List and India Office List By India Office, Great Britain #130]</ref>\n\n'''Personal Life'''\n \nAlfred William Begbie was born in 1801 at Hendon, Middlesex England. His parents were Peter Begbie & Frances (Jones) Begbie. \n\nAlfred William Begbie married Margaret Anna Grant  at Allahabad on 30 August 1825.  <ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:FGNC-84K \"India Marriages, 1792-1948 ,\" database, FamilySearch] Alfred William Begbie and Margaret Anna Grant, 30 Aug 1824; citing Allahabad, Bengal, India, reference ; FHL microfilm 498,981</ref>\n\nAlfred and Margaret had two daughters,  Frances Charlotte Begbie born in 1825 <ref> [https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:FG6M-26J \"India Births and Baptisms, 1786-1947,\" database, FamilySearch] Frances Charlotte Begbee, 21 Oct 1825; citing , reference ; FHL microfilm 498,955.</ref> and Emelia Georgeana Begbie born in 1826. <ref> [https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:FGDX-SGS \"India Births and Baptisms, 1786-1947,\" database, FamilySearch] Emelia Georgeana Bigbee, 20 Jan 1827; citing , reference ; FHL microfilm 498,957.</ref>\n\nMargaret Anna (Grant) Begbie passed away on 23 June 1828 at Humeerpore, India.  <ref>The Asiatic Journal and Monthly Miscellany, Volume 25; ''At Humpeerpore, the lady of A.W. Begbie Esq., of the civil service''</ref>\n\nAlfred married Charlotte Augusta Ricketts in 1831 at Humeerpore, Bengal, India. <ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:FGFB-NWT \"India Marriages, 1792-1948] ,\" database, FamilySearch: Alfred William Begbie and Charlotte Augusta Ricketts, 09 Jun 1831; citing Humeerpore, Bengal, India, reference ; FHL microfilm 498,964.</ref>\n\nCharlotte Augusta (Ricketts) Begbie passed away in 1833 at Zillah, Bengal, India. <ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:FGL7-FNY \"India Deaths and Burials, 1719-1948,\" database, FamilySearch] Charlotte Augusta Begbie, 22 Aug 1833; citing ; FHL microfilm 498,969.</ref>\n\nAlfred William Begbie married Margaret Watt (eldest daughter of the Isaac Watt, Esq., of Logie, Angusshire, Scotland) at Allahabad on 22 February 1836. <ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:FGN4-9X2 \"India Marriages, 1792-1948 ,\" database, FamilySearch]  :Alfred William Begbie and Margaret Watt, 22 Feb 1836; citing Allahabad, Bengal, India, reference ; FHL microfilm 498,973.</ref>\n\nAlfred and Margaret (Watt) Begbie had one daughter, Gertrude Emma Begbie who was born 20 February 1842. <ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:FG39-629 \"India Births and Baptisms, 1786-1947,\" database, FamilySearch] Gertrude Emma Begbie, 11 Mar 1842; citing , reference v 63 p 36; FHL microfilm 498,980. </ref>\n\nMargaret (Watt) Begbie passed away  in December 1842 and was buried 14 December 1842 at Landour, Bengal, India. <ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:FGPH-WW1  \"India Deaths and Burials, 1719-1948,\" database, FamilySearch] Begby, 14 Dec 1842; citing ; FHL microfilm 498,980. ''Begby (Female) was buried 14 December 1842 Landour, Bengal, India; Marital Status: Married: Spouse's Name: Begby''</ref>\n\nAlfred William Begbie married Lucy Sharp in 1848 at Simla, Bengal, India. <ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:FGN7-37N \"India Marriages, 1792-1948 ,\" database, FamilySearch] Alfred William Begbie and Lucy Sharp, 14 Oct 1848; citing Simla, Bengal, India, reference ; FHL microfilm 498,986.</ref>\n\nAlfred and Lucy (Sharp) had one son, Alfred John Begbie who was born 21 October 1849 at Chr. Agra, Bengal, India. <ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:FGQQ-8PX  \"India Births and Baptisms, 1786-1947,\" database, FamilySearch] Alfred John Begbie, 11 Jan 1850; citing CHR AGRA BENGAL INDIA, reference ; FHL microfilm 498,988. </ref>\n\nThe England Census of 1861 records: Alfred W Begbie age 59, occupation: Bengal Civil Service Retired, and his wife, Lucy Begbie age 57, and their children: Gertrude Emma Begbie age 19, Alfred John Begbie age 11, and their grandson, Alexander William D Campbell age 12 are living at Lansdowne Calvery Park Gardens, Tonbridge, Kent, England. The household employs three female servants and one male servant. <ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:Q2MP-DGG2 \"England and Wales Census, 1861,\" database with images, FamilySearch]</ref>  \n\nThe England Census of 1871 records: Alfred W Begbie age 69, born Hendon, Middlesex, occupation: Bengal Civil Service, and his wife, Lucy Begbie age 61, born Coventry Warwickshire, and their son Alfred J Begbie age 21, born East Indies, occupation: Undergraduate, are living at Tunbridge Wells, Tunbridge, Kent, England. Visiting them is Frederick A Sarthan age 20, born Manchester, Lancshire, occupation: Undergraduate. The household employs three female and one male servant. <ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:VF62-YXS \"England and Wales Census, 1871\", database with images, FamilySearch]</ref> \n\nAlfred William Begbie age 71,  passed away 05 June 1873 at Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England. <ref>[http://www.freebmd.org.uk/ Free BMD England & Wales BMD Registration Index 1837-2007] BEGBIE Alfred William age 71 died June q. 1873 at Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England (Vol. 2a Page\t298)</ref>\n\nHe left effects valued at under \u00a314,000. <ref> Probate of Will: [https://probatesearch.service.gov.uk/#wills  Probate Search UK \u2013 Find a Will] BEGBIE Alfred William Esq. Effects under \u00a314,000   18 July. The Will of Alfred William Begbie late of Tunbridge Wells in the County of Kent Esquire who died 05 June 1873 at Tunbridge Wells was proved at the Principal Registry by Lucy Begbie of Tunbridge Wells Widow the Relict the sole Executrix. </ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n[[File:PD-icon.svg|15px|link=|alt=]]&nbsp;''The above sources are in the [[public domain]].''\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{succession box \n| title=[[List of Lieutenant Governors of the North-Western Provinces|Lieutenant Governor of the North-Western Provinces]] <br> ''Acting''\n| before=[[James Thomason (British colonial governor)|James Thomason]] \n| after=[[John Russell Colvin|J. R. Colvin]] \n| years=10 October 1853 &ndash; 7 November 1853}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Begbie, A. W.}}\n[[Category:British East India Company civil servants]]\n[[Category:Lieutenant-Governors of the North-Western Provinces]]\n[[Category:1800 births]]\n[[Category:1889 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Sunset2607", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed full details of Probate of Will for privacy reasons these can be viewed from searching the link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfred_William_Begbie"}
{"title_page": "Johnny Clegg", "text_new": "{{redirect|Jonathan Clegg|the British rower|Jono Clegg}}\n{{similar names|John Clegg (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|South African musician and anti-apartheid icon}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name             = Johnny Clegg<br><small>[[Order of the British Empire|OBE]], [[Order of Ikhamanga|OIS]]</small>\n| image            = Johnny-clegg-valenciennes-davidata-14 07 2009.jpg\n| alt = Clegg singing and playing concertina\n| landscape        =\n| caption          = Clegg performing live in 2009\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Jonathan Paul Clegg\n| alias            = ''Le Zoulou Blanc''\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|df=yes|1953|6|7}}\n| birth_place      = [[Bacup]], Lancashire, England\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|2019|7|16|1953|6|7|df=yes}}\n| death_place      = [[Johannesburg]], [[South Africa]]\n| origin           = \n| instrument       = Vocals, guitar, [[concertina]]\n| genre            = [[Mbaqanga]], [[African popular music|Afro-pop]] <ref>{{cite web |title=Legendary musician Johnny Clegg has died |url=http://www.sabcnews.com/sabcnews/legendary-musician-johnny-clegg-has-died/ |website=SABC AFRICA |accessdate=8 October 2019}}</ref>\n| occupation       =  [[Musician]], [[Anthropologist]]\n| years_active     = 1976\u20132018\n| label            = [[Capitol Records]]<ref>{{cite web |title=South Africa's Johnny Clegg, with cancer in remission, to embark the Final Journey U.S. tour |url=https://www.mcall.com/la-et-ms-johnny-clegg-cancer-final-journey-us-tour-20170816-story.html |website=The Morning Call |accessdate=8 October 2019}}</ref>\n| associated_acts  = [[Juluka]], [[Savuka]]\n| website          = [http://www.johnnyclegg.com johnnyclegg.com]\n}}\n\n'''Jonathan Paul Clegg''', [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]], [[Order of Ikhamanga|OIS]] (7 June 1953 \u2013 16 July 2019) was a South African musician and [[anthropologist]], some of whose work was in musicology focused on the music of indigenous South African peoples.<ref name=sexton/> His band [[Juluka]] began as a duo with [[Sipho Mchunu]], and was the first group in the South African [[apartheid]]-era with a white man and a black man. They recorded and performed, later in larger formation.\n\nIn 1986 Clegg founded the band [[Savuka]], and also recorded as a solo act, occasionally reuniting with his earlier band partners. Sometimes called ''Le Zoulou Blanc'' ({{IPA-fr|l\u0259 zulu bl\u0251\u0303|lang}}, for \"The White [[Zulu people|Zulu]]\"), he was an important figure in South African popular music and one of the most prominent white activists in [[Internal resistance to apartheid|resistance to apartheid]],<ref name=LeMonde-Jul2019>{{cite web |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=16 July 2019 |title=Mort du chanteur sud-africain Johnny Clegg, \u00ab&nbsp;le Zoulou blanc&nbsp;\u00bb qui combattait l\u2019apartheid |url=https://www.lemonde.fr/disparitions/article/2019/07/16/mort-du-chanteur-sud-africain-johnny-clegg-le-zoulou-blanc-qui-combattait-l-apartheid_5490110_3382.html |website=Le Monde |location=Paris |trans-title=Death of South African singer Johnny Clegg, the \"white Zulu\" who fought apartheid |language=fr |agency=AFP |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716212749/https://www.lemonde.fr/disparitions/article/2019/07/16/mort-du-chanteur-sud-africain-johnny-clegg-le-zoulou-blanc-qui-combattait-l-apartheid_5490110_3382.html |archive-date=16 July 2019 |access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref> with songs that mixed [[Zulu language|Zulu]] and English lyrics, also combining [[Music of Africa|African music]] with various Western styles.<ref name=Cartwright-Jul2019>{{cite web |last=Cartwright |first=Gareth |date=24 July 2019 |title=Johnny Clegg: South African singer whose cross-cultural music was a direct challenge to apartheid |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/johnny-clegg-death-singer-south-africa-apartheid-nelson-mandela-obituary-a9008716.html |website=The Independent |location=London |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725142755/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/johnny-clegg-death-singer-south-africa-apartheid-nelson-mandela-obituary-a9008716.html |archive-date=25 July 2019 |access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nClegg was born on 7 June 1953 in [[Bacup]], [[Lancashire]],<ref name=\"official\">{{cite web|url=http://www.johnnyclegg.com/biog.html|title=JOHNNY CLEGG BIOGRAPHY AND AWARDS|publisher=JohnnyClegg.com|accessdate=2 July 2015}}</ref> to an English father of Scottish descent, Dennis Clegg, and a Rhodesian mother, Muriel (Braudo).<ref>{{cite web |author=<!--Not stated-->|date=22 July 2006 |title=White Zulu is making a comeback |url=https://www.iol.co.za/entertainment/celebrity-news/white-zulu-is-making-a-comeback-940896 |website=Independent Online (IOL) |location=Cape Town |access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=Cowell-Jul2019>{{cite web |last=Cowell |first=Alan |date=16 July 2019 |title=Johnny Clegg, South African Singer Who Battled Apartheid With Music, Is Dead at 66|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/16/arts/music/johnny-clegg-dead.html |website=The New York Times |access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> Clegg's mother's family were [[Jews|Jewish]] immigrants from [[Lithuania]], and Clegg had a secular Jewish upbringing, learning about the [[Ten Commandments]] but refusing to have a ''[[bar mitzvah]]'' or even associate with other Jewish children at school.<ref name=Bernarde-2003>{{cite book |last=Benarde |first=Scott R. |date=2003 |title=Stars of David: Rock'n'roll's Jewish Stories |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XI4-VnSrEcAC&pg=PA3 |publisher=Brandeis University Press |location=Waltham, MA |pages=3,279\u2013283 |isbn=1584653035 |access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> His parents divorced when he was still an infant, and he moved with his mother to Rhodesia (now [[Zimbabwe]]) and then, at the age of six, to South Africa,<ref name=\"people\">{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20100277,00.html|title=Black and White and Heard All Over, Johnny Clegg and Savuka Cross South Africa's Color Barrier|date=24 October 1988|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=People}}</ref> also spending part of a year in [[Israel]] during his childhood.<ref name=Bernarde-2003/>\n\nAs an adolescent in [[Johannesburg]]'s northern suburbs, he encountered the demi-monde of the city's Zulu migrant workers' music and dance. Under the tutelage of Charlie Mzila, a flat cleaner by day and musician by night, Clegg mastered both the [[Zulu language]] and the [[maskandi]] guitar and the isishameni dance styles of the migrants.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wits.ac.za/alumni/distinguished-graduates/honorary-degree-citations/johnny-clegg/|title=Johnny Clegg - Wits University|publisher=University of the Witwatersrand|language=en|access-date=2017-06-21}}</ref> Clegg's involvement with black musicians often led to arrests for trespassing on government property and for contravening the [[Group Areas Act]]. He was first arrested at the age of 15 for violating [[apartheid]]-era laws in South Africa banning people of different races from congregating together after curfew hours.<ref name=\"sassen\">{{cite news|url=http://www.popmatters.com/column/sassen021002/|first=Robyn|last=Sassen|date=16 October 2002|accessdate=2 July 2015|agency=PopMatters|title=Johnny Clegg: A South African Story}}</ref>\n\nAt the age of 17, he met [[Sipho Mchunu]], a Zulu migrant worker with whom he began performing music.<ref name=\"people\"/> The partnership, which they named [[Juluka]], was profiled in the 1970s television documentary ''[[Beats of the Heart: Rhythm of Resistance]]''.<ref name=\"beats\">''Beats of the Heart: Rhythm of Resistance'' (1979), dir. Jeremy Marre</ref>\n\nAfter graduating with a [[BA(Hons)]] in [[Social Anthropology]] from the [[University of Witwatersrand]], Clegg pursued an academic career for four years where he lectured and wrote several seminal scholarly papers on [[Zulu music]] and dance.<ref name=\":0\" /> In the early stages of his musical career, Clegg combined his music with the study of [[anthropology]]<ref name=\"beats\"/> at Wits, where he was influenced, among others, by the work of [[David Webster (anthropologist)|David Webster]], a [[social anthropology|social anthropologist]] who was later assassinated in 1989.<ref name=\"sassen\" /><ref name=\"wbur\">{{cite news|url=http://hereandnow.wbur.org/2014/04/28/johnny-clegg-music|title=Johnny Clegg On South Africa, Post-Mandela|date=28 April 2014|accessdate=2 July 2015|agency=WBUR}}</ref><ref name=\"latimes\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-08-12/entertainment/ca-23042_1_south-africa|title=South Africa's Johnny Clegg: A Witness to History|first=Randy|last=Lewis|date=12 August 1993|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n\nHe preceded each song with snippets of Zulu culture, information, commentary, humor and personal anecdotes relevant and unique to that song,<ref name=\":0\" /> occasionally also incorporating aspects of his Jewish roots in songs such as \"Jericho\", \"Jarusalema\" and \"Warsaw 1943\".<ref name=Bernarde-2003/>\n\n==Juluka==\nJuluka was an unusual musical partnership for the time in South Africa, with a white man (Clegg) and a black man (Mchunu) performing together. The band, which grew to a six-member group (with three white musicians and three black musicians) by the time it released its first album ''[[Universal Men]]'' in 1979, faced harassment and censorship, with Clegg later remarking that it was \"impossible\" to perform in public in South Africa.<ref name=\"carnival\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1996-07-18/entertainment/1996200008_1_juluka-johnny-clegg-south-africa|title=Clegg leads carnival of creativity|work=The Baltimore Sun|date=18 July 1996|accessdate=2 July 2015|first=Brian|last=Byrnes}}</ref> The group tested the apartheid-era laws, touring and performing in private venues, including universities, churches, hostels, and even private homes in order to attract an audience, as national broadcasters would not play their music.<ref name=\"official\"/>\n\nJust as unusually, the band's music combined Zulu, Celtic, and rock elements, with both [[English language|English]] and [[Zulu language|Zulu]] lyrics.<ref name=\"carnival\"/> Those lyrics often contained coded political messages and references to the battle against apartheid,<ref name=\"Korpe2004\">{{cite book|last=Korpe|first=Marie |title=Shoot the Singer!: Music Censorship Today|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-Yc0xnSfS8EC&pg=PA89|year=2004|publisher=Zed Books|isbn=978-1-84277-505-9|p=89}}</ref> although Clegg maintained that Juluka was not originally intended to be a political band. \"Politics found us,\" he told ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'' in 1996.<ref name=\"carnival\"/> In a 1989 interview with the ''[[Sunday Times (South Africa)|Sunday Times]]'', Clegg denied the label of \"political activist.\" \"For me a political activist is someone who has committed himself to a particular ideology. I don\u2019t belong to any political party. I stand for human rights.\"<ref>[[Jani Allan|Allan, Jani]]. Vive le Zoulou Blanc! That\u2019s how the French laud Johnny and make him top of their pops. ''Sunday Times'' (South Africa). 3 July 1988</ref>\n\nJuluka's music was both implicitly and explicitly political; not only was the fact of the success of the band (which openly celebrated African culture in a bi-racial band) a thorn in the flesh of a political system based on racial separation, the band also produced some explicitly political songs. For example, the album ''[[Work for All]]'' (which includes a song with the same title) picked up on [[Trade unions in South Africa|South African trade union]] slogans in the mid-1980s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://host.madison.com/news/opinion/column/john_nichols/john-nichols-the-singer-who-danced-with-mandela-returning-to/article_c6c8e086-6da9-54bc-af9b-dd2712cfbf4d.html|title=The singer who danced with Mandela returning to Madison|date=16 April 2014|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=The Cap Times|first=John|last=Nichols}}</ref> As a result of their political messages and racial integration, Clegg and other band members were arrested several times and concerts routinely broken up.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mg.co.za/article/2010-11-07-white-father-of-african-rock-marks-anniversary |title=White father of African rock marks anniversary|work=Mail & Guardian Online  |date= |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nDespite being ignored and often harassed by the South African government at home, Juluka were able to tour internationally, playing in [[Europe]], [[Canada]], and the [[United States]],<ref name=\"official\"/> and had two [[platinum album|platinum]] and five [[gold album]]s,<ref name=\"carnival\"/> becoming an international success. The group was disbanded in 1985, when Mchunu retired from music and went back to his family farm to return to his people's traditional life of raising cattle.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jul/16/johnny-clegg-south-african-singer-and-activist-dies-aged-66|title=Johnny Clegg, South African singer and activist, dies aged 66|date=July 16, 2019|accessdate=July 17, 2019|work=The Guardian}}</ref> It was briefly reconstituted when Mchunu and Clegg reunited in the mid-1990s, releasing [[Crocodile Love|one final album]] in 1997 before breaking up for good.<ref name=LeMonde-Jul2019/>\n\n==Savuka==\nTogether with the black musician and dancer [[Dudu Mntowaziwayo Ndlovu|Dudu Zulu]], Clegg went on to form his second inter-racial band, [[Savuka]], in 1986, continuing to blend African music with European influences.<ref name=\"people\"/><ref name=\"sassen\"/><ref name=\"carnival\"/> The group's first album, ''[[Third World Child]]'', broke international sales records in several European countries, including [[France]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wingate.edu/about-wingate/news/south-africas-johnny-clegg-brings-high-energy-music-to-wingate-university |title=South Africa's Johnny Clegg brings high-energy music to Wingate University |agency=Wingate University |date=17 March 2014 |accessdate=2 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703120739/http://www.wingate.edu/about-wingate/news/south-africas-johnny-clegg-brings-high-energy-music-to-wingate-university |archivedate=3 July 2015 }}</ref> The band went on to record several more albums, including ''[[Heat, Dust and Dreams]]'', which received a [[Grammy Award for Best World Music Album|Grammy Award]] nomination.<ref name=\"appleseed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.appleseedmusic.com/johnnyclegg/|title=Johnny Clegg|publisher=Appleseed Music|accessdate=2 July 2015}}</ref> Johnny Clegg and Savuka played both at home and abroad, even though Clegg's refusal to stop performing in apartheid-era South Africa created tensions with the international anti-apartheid movement. Despite his high-profile (and personally hazardous) opposition to the South African regime, this led to Clegg's expulsion from the [[Musicians' Union (UK)|British Musicians' Union]],<ref name=\"people\"/> in what one writer has since called \"a fit of pique\".<ref name=Cartwright-Jul2019/> In one instance, the band drew such a large crowd in [[Lyon]] that [[Michael Jackson]] cancelled a concert there, complaining that Clegg and his group had \"stole[n] all his fans\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.networkmedien.de/119-0-South-Africa-Cologne-Zulu-Festival-CD.html|title=Cologne Zulu Festival|agency=Works of Music - Network Medien|accessdate=2 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702220115/http://www.networkmedien.de/119-0-South-Africa-Cologne-Zulu-Festival-CD.html|archive-date=2 July 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1993, the band dissolved after Dudu Zulu was shot and killed while attempting to mediate a [[Taxi wars in South Africa|taxi war]].<ref name=\"sassen\"/><ref name=\"wbur\"/><ref name=\"carnival\"/>\n\n==Juluka reunion and solo career==\n[[File:JohnnyClegg Huma.jpg|thumb|Johnny Clegg at ''la f\u00eate de l'Humanit\u00e9'', France, 2007]]\nBriefly reunited in the mid-1990s, Clegg and Mchunu reformed Juluka, released [[Crocodile Love|a new album]],<ref name=\"appleseed\"/> and toured throughout the world in 1996 with [[King Sunny Ad\u00e9]].<ref name=\"tour\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1996-08-01/entertainment/ca-29967_1_political-situation|title=Band, in Tune With Politics, Back on Tour|date=1 August 1996|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|first=Bill|last=Locey}}</ref> In the following years, Clegg recorded several solo albums.  His touring schedule was abbreviated in 2017 after undergoing surgery for pancreatic cancer, and Clegg performed his last scheduled tour date in Mauritius in October 2018.<ref name=\"official\"/><ref name=\"wbur\"/>\n\nDuring one concert in 1999, he was joined onstage by South African President [[Nelson Mandela]], who danced as Johnny Clegg sang the protest song Savuka had dedicated to him, \"[[Asimbonanga]]\". Asimbonanga became an anthem of protest for the Mass Democratic Movement's umbrella organisation, the [[United Democratic Front (South Africa)|United Democratic Front]]. During Mandela's illness and death in 2013, the video of the concert attracted considerable media attention outside South Africa.<ref name=\"wbur\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2013/06/25/195472719/video-for-nelson-mandela-johnny-cleggs-asimbonanga|title=VIDEO For Nelson Mandela: Johnny Clegg's 'Asimbonanga'|date=25 June 2013|accessdate=2 July 2015|agency=[[National Public Radio]]}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nClegg's song \"Scatterlings of Africa\" gave him his only entries in the [[UK Singles Chart]] to date, reaching No. 44 in February 1983 with Juluka and No. 75 in May 1987 as Johnny Clegg and Savuka. The following year the song was featured on the soundtrack to the 1988 [[Academy Award|Oscar]]-winning film ''[[Rain Man]]''.<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= British Hit Singles & Albums\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited \n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 110}}</ref>\n\nHis song \"Life is a Magic Thing\" was featured in ''[[FernGully: The Last Rainforest]]''.<ref name=\"syracuse071719\">{{cite news|url=https://www.syracuse.com/celebrity-news/2019/07/johnny-clegg-dead-south-african-singer-heard-in-george-of-the-jungle-ferngully-was-66.html|agency=syracuse.com|title=Johnny Clegg dead: South African singer heard in 'George of the Jungle,' 'FernGully' was 66|date=July 17, 2019|accessdate=July 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSavuka's song \"Dela\" was featured on the soundtrack of the 1997 film ''[[George of the Jungle (film)|George of the Jungle]]'' and its 2003 sequel,<ref name=\"syracuse071719\"/> while \"Great Heart\" was the title song for the 1986 film ''[[Jock of the Bushveld]]''. \"Cruel, Crazy, Beautiful World\" was featured in the 1990 film ''[[Opportunity Knocks (film)|Opportunity Knocks]]'' and 1991 film ''[[Career Opportunities (film)|Career Opportunities]]''.<ref name=\"syracuse071719\"/>\n\n[[Jimmy Buffett]] recorded \"Great Heart\" for his 1988 album, ''[[Hot Water (Jimmy Buffett album)|Hot Water]]''.<ref name=sexton>{{cite news|last=Sexton|first=Paul|url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/news/johnny-clegg-dies-at-66/|agency=uDiscover Music|title=Johnny Clegg, South African Musical Hero And Anthropologist, Dies At 66|date=July 17, 2019|accessdate=July 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n* 1991: awarded the ''[[Legion d'Honneur|Chevalier des Arts et Lettres]]'' (Knight of Arts and Letters) by the [[Cabinet of France|French Government]].<ref name=\"Benselow\">{{cite web|last=Benselow|first=Robin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/jul/19/johnny-clegg-obituary |title=Johnny Clegg obituary / Singer-songwriter who used music to defy apartheid in South Africa |work=[[The Guardian]] |date= 19 July 2019 |accessdate=21 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 2004: voted 23rd in the [[SABC3's Great South Africans]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizcommunity.com/Article/196/423/4673.html|title=The 10 Greatest South Africans of all time|publisher=BizCommunity|date=27 September 2004|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref>\n* 2007: received an [[Honorary degree|honorary doctorate]] in music from the [[University of the Witwatersrand]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://web.wits.ac.za/NewsRoom/NewsItems/clegg.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-10-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080601024958/http://web.wits.ac.za/NewsRoom/NewsItems/clegg.htm |archivedate=1 June 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* 2011: received an honorary Doctor of Laws degree from [[City University of New York]] School of Law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.cuny.edu/mu/law/2011/04/15/human-rights-activist-jonathan-johnny-clegg-recieves-honorary-degree/ |title=Human Rights Activist, Jonathan \"Johnny\" Clegg {{sic|Recieves|nolink=y}} Honorary Degree \u2013 CUNY School of Law |publisher=.cuny.edu |date=15 April 2011 |accessdate=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n* 2012: received the [[Order of Ikhamanga]], Silver as part of the National Orders ceremony. This award is the highest honour a citizen can receive in South Africa. It was presented by President Jacob Zuma.<ref name=\"Benselow\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.news24.com/news24/SouthAfrica/Politics/National-orders-to-be-awarded-20120423 |title=National orders to be awarded &#124; News24 |publisher=M.news24.com |date=24 April 2012 |accessdate=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n* 2012: received an honorary Doctor of Humane Letters degree from [[Dartmouth College]], Hanover, NH, USA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dartmouth.edu/~commence/news/speeches/2012/clegg.html |title=Dartmouth Commencement 2012 \u2013 Johnny Clegg, Doctor of Humane Letters |publisher=Dartmouth.edu |date=10 June 2012 |accessdate=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n* 2013: received an honorary Doctorate in Music from the [[University of KwaZulu-Natal]], South Africa.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ukzn.ac.za/news//2013/04/17/-cultural-handyman-johnny-clegg-receives-honorary-doctorate |title='Music Legend' Johnny Clegg Receives Honorary Doctorate |publisher=Ukzn.ac.za |date=17 April 2013 |accessdate=14 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116084448/http://www.ukzn.ac.za/news//2013/04/17/-cultural-handyman-johnny-clegg-receives-honorary-doctorate |archivedate=16 January 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Honorary awards for their courageous contributions|url=http://www.iol.co.za/dailynews/news/honorary-awards-for-their-courageous-contributions-1.1501617#.VXxO0KFZ6PQ|accessdate=13 June 2015|work=Daily News|publisher=Independent Online|date=17 April 2013}}</ref>\n* 2015: was made an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]].<ref name=\"sape_John\">{{Cite web | title = Johnny Clegg Receives OBE for Services to South African Democracy  | author =  | work = SAPeople news | date = 27 November 2015 | accessdate = 2015-11-27 | url = http://www.sapeople.com/2015/11/26/johnny-clegg-receives-obe-for-services-to-south-african-democracy/ | quote = }}</ref><ref name=\"gov._HerM\">{{Cite web | title = Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth II Birthday Honours 2015 \u2013 South Africa  | author =  | work = gov.uk | date = 13 June 2015 | accessdate = 2015-12-02 | url = https://www.gov.uk/government/world-location-news/her-majesty-queen-elizabeth-ii-birthday-honours-2015-south-africa | quote =  }}</ref>\n* 2018: received an Honorary Doctorate of Philosophy Degree in Visual and Performing Arts from the [[Durban University of Technology]] alongside his Juluka bandmate, Sipho Mchunu.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dut.ac.za/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/johnny-speech-edited.pdf|title=The Durban University of Technology : 7 September 2018 : Mr Johnny Clegg|website=Dut.ac.za|accessdate=16 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Illness and death==\nJohnny Clegg was diagnosed with pancreatic cancer in 2015,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-johnny-clegg-cancer-final-journey-us-tour-20170816-story.html|title=South Africa's Johnny Clegg, with cancer in remission, to embark the Final Journey U.S. tour|date=2017-08-16|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2017-11-14|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref> which ultimately led to his death on 16 July 2019. He died in his Johannesburg home surrounded by loved ones and was laid to rest the following day in [[Westpark Cemetery]] in Johannesburg.<ref>{{cite web |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=16 July 2019 |title=Legendary artist Johnny Clegg dies at 66 |url= https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/gauteng/legendary-artist-johnny-clegg-dies-at-66-29321787\n|website=Independent Online (IOL) |location=Cape Town |access-date=17 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Remembering a legend: 9 of Johnny Clegg's biggest hits |url=https://www.channel24.co.za/Music/News/remembering-a-legend-9-of-johnny-cleggs-biggest-hits-20190716? |accessdate=16 July 2019 |work=Channel |date=16 July 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Clegg is survived by his wife, Jenny, and his two sons, Jesse and Jaron.\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite journal|last=Clegg|first=Jonathan|year=1981|title=Ukubuyisa Isidumbu \u2013 \"Bringing back the body\": An examination into the ideology of vengeance in the Msinga and Mpofana rural locations(1882\u20131944)|journal=African Studies Seminar Series|publisher=African Studies Institute|location=Johannesburg|hdl=10539/8496}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Clegg|first=Jonathan|year=1981|title=The Music of Zulu Immigrant Workers in Johannesburg: A Focus on Concertina and Guitar|journal=Papers Presented at the Symposium on Ethnomusicology|publisher=[[International Library of African Music]]|location=[[Grahamstown]]|editor-link=Andrew Tracey|editor-first=Andrew |editor-last=Tracey}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Clegg|first=Jonathan|year=1982|title=Towards an understanding of African Dance: The Zulu Isishameni Style|journal=Papers Read at Second Symposium on Ethnomusicology, 24\u201326 September 1981, Rhodes University, Grahamstown, South Africa|publisher=Institute of Social and Economic Research|location=[[Grahamstown]]|editor-link=Andrew Tracey|editor-first=Andrew |editor-last=Tracey}}\n*{{cite conference |last=Clegg |first=Jonathan |date=1984 |title=Examination of the Umzansi dance style |book-title=Papers presented at the Third and Fourth symposia on Ethnomusicology: Music Department, University of Natal, Durban, 16th to 19th September 1982; Music Department, Rhodes University, 7th to 8th October 1983 |publisher=Institute of Social and Economic Research |location=Grahamstown |editor-link=Andrew Tracey |editor-first=Andrew |editor-last=Tracey |oclc=13658380 |isbn=086810096X}}\n\n==Discography==\n{{See also|Juluka#Discography|Savuka#Selected music}}\n\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; width:10px;\"|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; width:320px;\"|Album\n!  style=\"text-align:center; width:20px;\"|Peak positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\" | [[SNEP|FRA]]<br><ref name=\"fr\">{{cite web | url=http://lescharts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Johnny+Clegg | title=Johnny Clegg discography | publisher=Hung Medien | work=lescharts.com |accessdate=21 December 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1985\n| ''Third World Child (Johnny Clegg solo album)''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2002\n|''New World Survivor''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2006\n|''[[One Life (Johnny Clegg album)|One Life]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|150\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2010\n|''Human''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|109\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2017\n|''King of Time''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|}\n\n===Live albums===\n* 2003: ''[[A South African Story - Live at the Nelson Mandela Theatre]]''<ref>{{cite web\n| url = https://www.allmusic.com/album/a-south-african-story-live-at-the-nelson-mandela-theatre-mw0001439624\n| title =  Johnny Clegg / A South African Story: Live at the Nelson Mandela Theatre \n| website = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = 21 July 2019\n}}</ref>\n* 2003: ''[[Best of Live (Johnny Clegg)|Best of Live]]''<ref>{{cite web\n| url = https://www.allmusic.com/album/best-of-live-at-the-nelson-mandela-theather-mw0000468276\n| title = Best of Live\n| website = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = 21 July 2019\n}}</ref>\n* 2014: ''[[Best, Live & Unplugged At The Baxter Theatre Cape Town]]''<ref>{{cite web\n| last = Leggett\n| first = Steve\n| url = https://www.allmusic.com/album/best-live-unplugged-at-the-baxter-theatre-cape-town-mw0002636199\n| title = Best, Live & Unplugged: At the Baxter Theatre Cape Town\n| website = [[AllMusic]]\n| accessdate = 21 July 2019\n}}</ref>\n\n===DVD===\n* 2004: ''[[Live! and more...]]''<ref>{{cite book\n| last = Larkin\n| first = Colin\n| url = https://books.google.de/books?id=_NNmFiUnSmUC&pg=PA183\n| title = Clegg, Johnny\n| work = The Encyclopedia of Popular Music\n| publisher = Omnibus Press\n| year = 2011\n| pages = 183\u2013185\n| isbn = 978-0-85-712595-8\n}}</ref>\n<!--* 2006: ''[[Johnny Clegg Live at the Nelson Mandela Theatre]]''{{cn|date=October 2018}} - getting tired, may be 2007 {{cn|date=October 2018}}-->\n* 2010: ''[[Johnny Clegg 30th Anniversary Concert at Emmarentia Dam]]''<ref name=\"fr\" />\n\n===Soundtracks===\n* 1992: ''[[The Power of One (soundtrack)|The Power of One]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=The Power of One (1992)|url=http://www.soundtrackinfo.com/title/powerofone.asp|work=soundtrackinfo.com|publisher=The Soundtrack Info Project|accessdate=15 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Remembering Johnny Clegg's Powerful Mission / South Africa's best-known musician has dedicated his life to crossing the lines separating white and black|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/johnny-clegg-apartheid-south-africa-860407/|work=rollingstone.com|publisher=RollingStone|accessdate=21 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official}}\n* [http://inmyafricandream.free.fr/ In My African Dream: the Johnny Clegg Discography] inmyafricandream.free.fr\n* Greg Kot: [https://web.archive.org/web/20050913023809/http://www.talkingleaves.com/articles/worlds.html Worlds Apart: Johnny Clegg Has Been / Molded by South Africa] [[Chicago Tribune]] April 29, 1990\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927191703/http://www.talkingleaves.com/pithouse.html A National Treasure Turns 21] talkingleaves.com October 25, 2000\n* Jeremy Cooper: [https://web.archive.org/web/20070223235202/http://www.chico.mweb.co.za/art/2006/2006dec/061215-zulu.html The return of the white Zulu] chico.mweb.co 15 December 2006\n* {{discogs artist}}\n* {{Find a Grave|201345469}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clegg, Johnny}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Jewish South African anti-apartheid activists]]\n[[Category:White South African anti-apartheid activists]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to Rhodesia]]\n[[Category:Rhodesian emigrants to South Africa]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records artists]]\n[[Category:Concertina players]]\n[[Category:Jewish English musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Bacup]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Ikhamanga]]\n[[Category:South African anthropologists]]\n[[Category:South African musicians]]\n[[Category:Secular Jews]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to South Africa]]\n[[Category:South African people of English-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:South African people of Lithuanian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:South African people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:South African people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:South African people of Zimbabwean descent]]\n[[Category:South African pop singers]]\n[[Category:University of the Witwatersrand alumni]]\n[[Category:Juluka members]]\n[[Category:Savuka members]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pancreatic cancer]]\n[[Category:English people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Lithuanian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Zimbabwean descent]]\n[[Category:Burials at Westpark Cemetery]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Jonathan Clegg|the British rower|Jono Clegg}}\n{{similar names|John Clegg (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|South African musician and anti-apartheid icon}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name             = Johnny Clegg<br><small>[[Order of the British Empire|OBE]], [[Order of Ikhamanga|OIS]]</small>\n| image            = Johnny-clegg-valenciennes-davidata-14 07 2009.jpg\n| alt = Clegg singing and playing concertina\n| landscape        =\n| caption          = Clegg performing live in 2009\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Jonathan Paul Clegg\n| alias            = ''Le Zoulou Blanc''\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|df=yes|1953|6|7}}\n| birth_place      = [[Bacup]], Lancashire, England\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|2019|7|16|1953|6|7|df=yes}}\n| death_place      = [[Johannesburg]], [[South Africa]]\n| origin           = \n| instrument       = Vocals, guitar, [[concertina]]\n| genre            = [[Mbaqanga]], [[African popular music|Afro-pop]] <ref>{{cite web |title=Legendary musician Johnny Clegg has died |url=http://www.sabcnews.com/sabcnews/legendary-musician-johnny-clegg-has-died/ |website=SABC AFRICA |accessdate=8 October 2019}}</ref>\n| occupation       =  [[Musician]], [[Anthropologist]]\n| years_active     = 1976\u20132018\n| label            = [[Capitol Records]]<ref>{{cite web |title=South Africa's Johnny Clegg, with cancer in remission, to embark the Final Journey U.S. tour |url=https://www.mcall.com/la-et-ms-johnny-clegg-cancer-final-journey-us-tour-20170816-story.html |website=The Morning Call |accessdate=8 October 2019}}</ref>\n| associated_acts  = [[Juluka]], [[Savuka]]\n| website          = [http://www.johnnyclegg.com johnnyclegg.com]\n}}\n\n'''Jonathan Paul Clegg''', [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]], [[Order of Ikhamanga|OIS]] (7 June 1953 \u2013 16 July 2019) was a South African musician and [[anthropologist]], some of whose work was in musicology focused on the music of indigenous South African peoples.<ref name=sexton/> His band [[Juluka]] began as a duo with [[Sipho Mchunu]], and was the first group in the South African [[apartheid]]-era with a white man and a black man. They recorded and performed, later in larger formation.\n\nIn 1986 Clegg founded the band [[Savuka]], and also recorded as a solo act, occasionally reuniting with his earlier band partners. Sometimes called ''Le Zoulou Blanc'' ({{IPA-fr|l\u0259 zulu bl\u0251\u0303|lang}}, for \"The White [[Zulu people|Zulu]]\"), he was an important figure in South African popular music and one of the most prominent white activists in [[Internal resistance to apartheid|resistance to apartheid]],<ref name=LeMonde-Jul2019>{{cite web |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=16 July 2019 |title=Mort du chanteur sud-africain Johnny Clegg, \u00ab&nbsp;le Zoulou blanc&nbsp;\u00bb qui combattait l\u2019apartheid |url=https://www.lemonde.fr/disparitions/article/2019/07/16/mort-du-chanteur-sud-africain-johnny-clegg-le-zoulou-blanc-qui-combattait-l-apartheid_5490110_3382.html |website=Le Monde |location=Paris |trans-title=Death of South African singer Johnny Clegg, the \"white Zulu\" who fought apartheid |language=fr |agency=AFP |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716212749/https://www.lemonde.fr/disparitions/article/2019/07/16/mort-du-chanteur-sud-africain-johnny-clegg-le-zoulou-blanc-qui-combattait-l-apartheid_5490110_3382.html |archive-date=16 July 2019 |access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref> with songs that mixed [[Zulu language|Zulu]] and English lyrics, also combining [[Music of Africa|African music]] with various Western styles.<ref name=Cartwright-Jul2019>{{cite web |last=Cartwright |first=Gareth |date=24 July 2019 |title=Johnny Clegg: South African singer whose cross-cultural music was a direct challenge to apartheid |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/johnny-clegg-death-singer-south-africa-apartheid-nelson-mandela-obituary-a9008716.html |website=The Independent |location=London |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725142755/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/johnny-clegg-death-singer-south-africa-apartheid-nelson-mandela-obituary-a9008716.html |archive-date=25 July 2019 |access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nClegg was born on 7 June 1953 in [[Bacup]], [[Lancashire]],<ref name=\"official\">{{cite web|url=http://www.johnnyclegg.com/biog.html|title=JOHNNY CLEGG BIOGRAPHY AND AWARDS|publisher=JohnnyClegg.com|accessdate=2 July 2015}}</ref> to an English father of Scottish descent, Dennis Clegg, and a Rhodesian mother, Muriel (Braudo).<ref>{{cite web |author=<!--Not stated-->|date=22 July 2006 |title=White Zulu is making a comeback |url=https://www.iol.co.za/entertainment/celebrity-news/white-zulu-is-making-a-comeback-940896 |website=Independent Online (IOL) |location=Cape Town |access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=Cowell-Jul2019>{{cite web |last=Cowell |first=Alan |date=16 July 2019 |title=Johnny Clegg, South African Singer Who Battled Apartheid With Music, Is Dead at 66|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/16/arts/music/johnny-clegg-dead.html |website=The New York Times |access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> Clegg's mother's family were [[Jews|Jewish]] immigrants from [[Lithuania]], and Clegg had a secular Jewish upbringing, learning about the [[Ten Commandments]] but refusing to have a ''[[bar mitzvah]]'' or even associate with other Jewish children at school.<ref name=Bernarde-2003>{{cite book |last=Benarde |first=Scott R. |date=2003 |title=Stars of David: Rock'n'roll's Jewish Stories |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XI4-VnSrEcAC&pg=PA3 |publisher=Brandeis University Press |location=Waltham, MA |pages=3,279\u2013283 |isbn=1584653035 |access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> His parents divorced when he was still an infant, and he moved with his mother to Rhodesia (now [[Zimbabwe]]) and then, at the age of six, to South Africa,<ref name=\"people\">{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20100277,00.html|title=Black and White and Heard All Over, Johnny Clegg and Savuka Cross South Africa's Color Barrier|date=24 October 1988|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=People}}</ref> also spending part of a year in [[Israel]] during his childhood.<ref name=Bernarde-2003/>\n\nAs an adolescent in [[Johannesburg]]'s northern suburbs, he encountered the demi-monde of the city's Zulu migrant workers' music and dance. Under the tutelage of Charlie Mzila, a flat cleaner by day and musician by night, Clegg mastered both the [[Zulu language]] and the [[maskandi]] guitar and the isishameni dance styles of the migrants.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wits.ac.za/alumni/distinguished-graduates/honorary-degree-citations/johnny-clegg/|title=Johnny Clegg - Wits University|publisher=University of the Witwatersrand|language=en|access-date=2017-06-21}}</ref> Clegg's involvement with black musicians often led to arrests for trespassing on government property and for contravening the [[Group Areas Act]]. He was first arrested at the age of 15 for violating [[apartheid]]-era laws in South Africa banning people of different races from congregating together after curfew hours.<ref name=\"sassen\">{{cite news|url=http://www.popmatters.com/column/sassen021002/|first=Robyn|last=Sassen|date=16 October 2002|accessdate=2 July 2015|agency=PopMatters|title=Johnny Clegg: A South African Story}}</ref>\n\nAt the age of 17, he met [[Sipho Mchunu]], a Zulu migrant worker with whom he began performing music.<ref name=\"people\"/> The partnership, which they named [[Juluka]], was profiled in the 1970s television documentary ''[[Beats of the Heart: Rhythm of Resistance]]''.<ref name=\"beats\">''Beats of the Heart: Rhythm of Resistance'' (1979), dir. Jeremy Marre</ref>\n\nAfter graduating with a [[BA(Hons)]] in [[Social Anthropology]] from the [[University of Witwatersrand]], Clegg pursued an academic career for four years where he lectured and wrote several seminal scholarly papers on [[Zulu music]] and dance.<ref name=\":0\" /> In the early stages of his musical career, Clegg combined his music with the study of [[anthropology]]<ref name=\"beats\"/> at Wits, where he was influenced, among others, by the work of [[David Webster (anthropologist)|David Webster]], a [[social anthropology|social anthropologist]] who was later assassinated in 1989.<ref name=\"sassen\" /><ref name=\"wbur\">{{cite news|url=http://hereandnow.wbur.org/2014/04/28/johnny-clegg-music|title=Johnny Clegg On South Africa, Post-Mandela|date=28 April 2014|accessdate=2 July 2015|agency=WBUR}}</ref><ref name=\"latimes\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-08-12/entertainment/ca-23042_1_south-africa|title=South Africa's Johnny Clegg: A Witness to History|first=Randy|last=Lewis|date=12 August 1993|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n\nHe preceded each song with snippets of Zulu culture, information, commentary, humor and personal anecdotes relevant and unique to that song,<ref name=\":0\" /> occasionally also incorporating aspects of his Jewish roots in songs such as \"Jericho\", \"Jarusalema\" and \"Warsaw 1943\".<ref name=Bernarde-2003/>\n\n==Juluka==\nJuluka was an unusual musical partnership for the time in South Africa, with a white man (Clegg) and a black man (Mchunu) performing together. The band, which grew to a six-member group (with three white musicians and three black musicians) by the time it released its first album ''[[Universal Men]]'' in 1979, faced harassment and censorship, with Clegg later remarking that it was \"impossible\" to perform in public in South Africa.<ref name=\"carnival\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1996-07-18/entertainment/1996200008_1_juluka-johnny-clegg-south-africa|title=Clegg leads carnival of creativity|work=The Baltimore Sun|date=18 July 1996|accessdate=2 July 2015|first=Brian|last=Byrnes}}</ref> The group tested the apartheid-era laws, touring and performing in private venues, including universities, churches, hostels, and even private homes in order to attract an audience, as national broadcasters would not play their music.<ref name=\"official\"/>\n\nJust as unusually, the band's music combined Zulu, Celtic, and rock elements, with both [[English language|English]] and [[Zulu language|Zulu]] lyrics.<ref name=\"carnival\"/> Those lyrics often contained coded political messages and references to the battle against apartheid,<ref name=\"Korpe2004\">{{cite book|last=Korpe|first=Marie |title=Shoot the Singer!: Music Censorship Today|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-Yc0xnSfS8EC&pg=PA89|year=2004|publisher=Zed Books|isbn=978-1-84277-505-9|p=89}}</ref> although Clegg maintained that Juluka was not originally intended to be a political band. \"Politics found us,\" he told ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'' in 1996.<ref name=\"carnival\"/> In a 1989 interview with the ''[[Sunday Times (South Africa)|Sunday Times]]'', Clegg denied the label of \"political activist.\" \"For me a political activist is someone who has committed himself to a particular ideology. I don\u2019t belong to any political party. I stand for human rights.\"<ref>[[Jani Allan|Allan, Jani]]. Vive le Zoulou Blanc! That\u2019s how the French laud Johnny and make him top of their pops. ''Sunday Times'' (South Africa). 3 July 1988</ref>\n\nJuluka's music was both implicitly and explicitly political; not only was the fact of the success of the band (which openly celebrated African culture in a bi-racial band) a thorn in the flesh of a political system based on racial separation, the band also produced some explicitly political songs. For example, the album ''[[Work for All]]'' (which includes a song with the same title) picked up on [[Trade unions in South Africa|South African trade union]] slogans in the mid-1980s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://host.madison.com/news/opinion/column/john_nichols/john-nichols-the-singer-who-danced-with-mandela-returning-to/article_c6c8e086-6da9-54bc-af9b-dd2712cfbf4d.html|title=The singer who danced with Mandela returning to Madison|date=16 April 2014|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=The Cap Times|first=John|last=Nichols}}</ref> As a result of their political messages and racial integration, Clegg and other band members were arrested several times and concerts routinely broken up.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mg.co.za/article/2010-11-07-white-father-of-african-rock-marks-anniversary |title=White father of African rock marks anniversary|work=Mail & Guardian Online  |date= |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nDespite being ignored and often harassed by the South African government at home, Juluka were able to tour internationally, playing in [[Europe]], [[Canada]], and the [[United States]],<ref name=\"official\"/> and had two [[platinum album|platinum]] and five [[gold album]]s,<ref name=\"carnival\"/> becoming an international success. The group was disbanded in 1985, when Mchunu retired from music and went back to his family farm to return to his people's traditional life of raising cattle.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jul/16/johnny-clegg-south-african-singer-and-activist-dies-aged-66|title=Johnny Clegg, South African singer and activist, dies aged 66|date=July 16, 2019|accessdate=July 17, 2019|work=The Guardian}}</ref> It was briefly reconstituted when Mchunu and Clegg reunited in the mid-1990s, releasing [[Crocodile Love|one final album]] in 1997 before breaking up for good.<ref name=LeMonde-Jul2019/>\n\n==Savuka==\nTogether with the black musician and dancer [[Dudu Mntowaziwayo Ndlovu|Dudu Zulu]], Clegg went on to form his second inter-racial band, [[Savuka]], in 1986, continuing to blend African music with European influences.<ref name=\"people\"/><ref name=\"sassen\"/><ref name=\"carnival\"/> The group's first album, ''[[Third World Child]]'', broke international sales records in several European countries, including [[France]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wingate.edu/about-wingate/news/south-africas-johnny-clegg-brings-high-energy-music-to-wingate-university |title=South Africa's Johnny Clegg brings high-energy music to Wingate University |agency=Wingate University |date=17 March 2014 |accessdate=2 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703120739/http://www.wingate.edu/about-wingate/news/south-africas-johnny-clegg-brings-high-energy-music-to-wingate-university |archivedate=3 July 2015 }}</ref> The band went on to record several more albums, including ''[[Heat, Dust and Dreams]]'', which received a [[Grammy Award for Best World Music Album|Grammy Award]] nomination.<ref name=\"appleseed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.appleseedmusic.com/johnnyclegg/|title=Johnny Clegg|publisher=Appleseed Music|accessdate=2 July 2015}}</ref> Johnny Clegg and Savuka played both at home and abroad, even though Clegg's refusal to stop performing in apartheid-era South Africa created tensions with the international anti-apartheid movement. Despite his high-profile (and personally hazardous) opposition to the South African regime, this led to Clegg's expulsion from the [[Musicians' Union (UK)|British Musicians' Union]],<ref name=\"people\"/> in what one writer has since called \"a fit of pique\".<ref name=Cartwright-Jul2019/> In one instance, the band drew such a large crowd in [[Lyon]] that [[Michael Jackson]] cancelled a concert there, complaining that Clegg and his group had \"stole[n] all his fans\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.networkmedien.de/119-0-South-Africa-Cologne-Zulu-Festival-CD.html|title=Cologne Zulu Festival|agency=Works of Music - Network Medien|accessdate=2 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702220115/http://www.networkmedien.de/119-0-South-Africa-Cologne-Zulu-Festival-CD.html|archive-date=2 July 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1993, the band dissolved after Dudu Zulu was shot and killed while attempting to mediate a [[Taxi wars in South Africa|taxi war]].<ref name=\"sassen\"/><ref name=\"wbur\"/><ref name=\"carnival\"/>\n\n==Juluka reunion and solo career==\n[[File:JohnnyClegg Huma.jpg|thumb|Johnny Clegg at ''la f\u00eate de l'Humanit\u00e9'', France, 2007]]\nBriefly reunited in the mid-1990s, Clegg and Mchunu reformed Juluka, released [[Crocodile Love|a new album]],<ref name=\"appleseed\"/> and toured throughout the world in 1996 with [[King Sunny Ad\u00e9]].<ref name=\"tour\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1996-08-01/entertainment/ca-29967_1_political-situation|title=Band, in Tune With Politics, Back on Tour|date=1 August 1996|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|first=Bill|last=Locey}}</ref> In the following years, Clegg recorded several solo albums.  His touring schedule was abbreviated in 2017 after undergoing surgery for pancreatic cancer, and Clegg performed his last scheduled tour date in Mauritius in October 2018.<ref name=\"official\"/><ref name=\"wbur\"/>\n\nDuring one concert in 1999, he was joined onstage by South African President [[Nelson Mandela]], who danced as Johnny Clegg sang the protest song Savuka had dedicated to him, \"[[Asimbonanga]]\". Asimbonanga became an anthem of protest for the Mass Democratic Movement's umbrella organisation, the [[United Democratic Front (South Africa)|United Democratic Front]]. During Mandela's illness and death in 2013, the video of the concert attracted considerable media attention outside South Africa.<ref name=\"wbur\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2013/06/25/195472719/video-for-nelson-mandela-johnny-cleggs-asimbonanga|title=VIDEO For Nelson Mandela: Johnny Clegg's 'Asimbonanga'|date=25 June 2013|accessdate=2 July 2015|agency=[[National Public Radio]]}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nClegg's song \"Scatterlings of Africa\" gave him his only entries in the [[UK Singles Chart]] to date, reaching No. 44 in February 1983 with Juluka and No. 75 in May 1987 as Johnny Clegg and Savuka. The following year the song was featured on the soundtrack to the 1988 [[Academy Award|Oscar]]-winning film ''[[Rain Man]]''.<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= British Hit Singles & Albums\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited \n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 110}}</ref>\n\nHis song \"Life is a Magic Thing\" was featured in ''[[FernGully: The Last Rainforest]]''.<ref name=\"syracuse071719\">{{cite news|url=https://www.syracuse.com/celebrity-news/2019/07/johnny-clegg-dead-south-african-singer-heard-in-george-of-the-jungle-ferngully-was-66.html|agency=syracuse.com|title=Johnny Clegg dead: South African singer heard in 'George of the Jungle,' 'FernGully' was 66|date=July 17, 2019|accessdate=July 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSavuka's song \"Dela\" was featured on the soundtrack of the 1997 film ''[[George of the Jungle (film)|George of the Jungle]]'' and its 2003 sequel,<ref name=\"syracuse071719\"/> while \"Great Heart\" was the title song for the 1986 film ''[[Jock of the Bushveld]]''. \"Cruel, Crazy, Beautiful World\" was featured in the 1990 film ''[[Opportunity Knocks (film)|Opportunity Knocks]]'' and 1991 film ''[[Career Opportunities (film)|Career Opportunities]]''.<ref name=\"syracuse071719\"/>\n\n[[Jimmy Buffett]] recorded \"Great Heart\" for his 1988 album, ''[[Hot Water (Jimmy Buffett album)|Hot Water]]''.<ref name=sexton>{{cite news|last=Sexton|first=Paul|url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/news/johnny-clegg-dies-at-66/|agency=uDiscover Music|title=Johnny Clegg, South African Musical Hero And Anthropologist, Dies At 66|date=July 17, 2019|accessdate=July 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n* 1991: awarded the ''[[Legion d'Honneur|Chevalier des Arts et Lettres]]'' (Knight of Arts and Letters) by the [[Cabinet of France|French Government]].<ref name=\"Benselow\">{{cite web|last=Benselow|first=Robin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/jul/19/johnny-clegg-obituary |title=Johnny Clegg obituary / Singer-songwriter who used music to defy apartheid in South Africa |work=[[The Guardian]] |date= 19 July 2019 |accessdate=21 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 2004: voted 23rd in the [[SABC3's Great South Africans]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizcommunity.com/Article/196/423/4673.html|title=The 10 Greatest South Africans of all time|publisher=BizCommunity|date=27 September 2004|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref>\n* 2007: received an [[Honorary degree|honorary doctorate]] in music from the [[University of the Witwatersrand]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://web.wits.ac.za/NewsRoom/NewsItems/clegg.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-10-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080601024958/http://web.wits.ac.za/NewsRoom/NewsItems/clegg.htm |archivedate=1 June 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* 2011: received an honorary Doctor of Laws degree from [[City University of New York]] School of Law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.cuny.edu/mu/law/2011/04/15/human-rights-activist-jonathan-johnny-clegg-recieves-honorary-degree/ |title=Human Rights Activist, Jonathan \"Johnny\" Clegg {{sic|Recieves|nolink=y}} Honorary Degree \u2013 CUNY School of Law |publisher=.cuny.edu |date=15 April 2011 |accessdate=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n* 2012: received the [[Order of Ikhamanga]], Silver as part of the National Orders ceremony. This award is the highest honour a citizen can receive in South Africa. It was presented by President Jacob Zuma.<ref name=\"Benselow\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.news24.com/news24/SouthAfrica/Politics/National-orders-to-be-awarded-20120423 |title=National orders to be awarded &#124; News24 |publisher=M.news24.com |date=24 April 2012 |accessdate=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n* 2012: received an honorary Doctor of Humane Letters degree from [[Dartmouth College]], Hanover, NH, USA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dartmouth.edu/~commence/news/speeches/2012/clegg.html |title=Dartmouth Commencement 2012 \u2013 Johnny Clegg, Doctor of Humane Letters |publisher=Dartmouth.edu |date=10 June 2012 |accessdate=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n* 2013: received an honorary Doctorate in Music from the [[University of KwaZulu-Natal]], South Africa.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ukzn.ac.za/news//2013/04/17/-cultural-handyman-johnny-clegg-receives-honorary-doctorate |title='Music Legend' Johnny Clegg Receives Honorary Doctorate |publisher=Ukzn.ac.za |date=17 April 2013 |accessdate=14 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116084448/http://www.ukzn.ac.za/news//2013/04/17/-cultural-handyman-johnny-clegg-receives-honorary-doctorate |archivedate=16 January 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Honorary awards for their courageous contributions|url=http://www.iol.co.za/dailynews/news/honorary-awards-for-their-courageous-contributions-1.1501617#.VXxO0KFZ6PQ|accessdate=13 June 2015|work=Daily News|publisher=Independent Online|date=17 April 2013}}</ref>\n* 2015: was made an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]].<ref name=\"sape_John\">{{Cite web | title = Johnny Clegg Receives OBE for Services to South African Democracy  | author =  | work = SAPeople news | date = 27 November 2015 | accessdate = 2015-11-27 | url = http://www.sapeople.com/2015/11/26/johnny-clegg-receives-obe-for-services-to-south-african-democracy/ | quote = }}</ref><ref name=\"gov._HerM\">{{Cite web | title = Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth II Birthday Honours 2015 \u2013 South Africa  | author =  | work = gov.uk | date = 13 June 2015 | accessdate = 2015-12-02 | url = https://www.gov.uk/government/world-location-news/her-majesty-queen-elizabeth-ii-birthday-honours-2015-south-africa | quote =  }}</ref>\n* 2018: received an Honorary Doctorate of Philosophy Degree in Visual and Performing Arts from the [[Durban University of Technology]] alongside his Juluka bandmate, Sipho Mchunu.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dut.ac.za/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/johnny-speech-edited.pdf|title=The Durban University of Technology : 7 September 2018 : Mr Johnny Clegg|website=Dut.ac.za|accessdate=16 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Illness and death==\nJohnny Clegg was diagnosed with pancreatic cancer in 2015,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-johnny-clegg-cancer-final-journey-us-tour-20170816-story.html|title=South Africa's Johnny Clegg, with cancer in remission, to embark the Final Journey U.S. tour|date=2017-08-16|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2017-11-14|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref> which ultimately led to his death on 16 July 2019. He died in his Johannesburg home surrounded by loved ones and was laid to rest the following day in [[Westpark Cemetery]] in Johannesburg.<ref>{{cite web  | url         = https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/gauteng/legendary-artist-johnny-clegg-dies-at-66-29321787 | title = Legendary artist Johnny Clegg dies at 66 | date = 2019-07-16\n | website = | publisher = iol.co.za | accessdate = 2019-07-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Remembering a legend: 9 of Johnny Clegg's biggest hits |url=https://www.channel24.co.za/Music/News/remembering-a-legend-9-of-johnny-cleggs-biggest-hits-20190716? |accessdate=16 July 2019 |work=Channel |date=16 July 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Clegg is survived by his wife, Jenny, and his two sons, Jesse and Jaron.\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite journal|last=Clegg|first=Jonathan|year=1981|title=Ukubuyisa Isidumbu \u2013 \"Bringing back the body\": An examination into the ideology of vengeance in the Msinga and Mpofana rural locations(1882\u20131944)|journal=African Studies Seminar Series|publisher=African Studies Institute|location=Johannesburg|hdl=10539/8496}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Clegg|first=Jonathan|year=1981|title=The Music of Zulu Immigrant Workers in Johannesburg: A Focus on Concertina and Guitar|journal=Papers Presented at the Symposium on Ethnomusicology|publisher=[[International Library of African Music]]|location=[[Grahamstown]]|editor-link=Andrew Tracey|editor-first=Andrew |editor-last=Tracey}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Clegg|first=Jonathan|year=1982|title=Towards an understanding of African Dance: The Zulu Isishameni Style|journal=Papers Read at Second Symposium on Ethnomusicology, 24\u201326 September 1981, Rhodes University, Grahamstown, South Africa|publisher=Institute of Social and Economic Research|location=[[Grahamstown]]|editor-link=Andrew Tracey|editor-first=Andrew |editor-last=Tracey}}\n*{{cite conference |last=Clegg |first=Jonathan |date=1984 |title=Examination of the Umzansi dance style |book-title=Papers presented at the Third and Fourth symposia on Ethnomusicology: Music Department, University of Natal, Durban, 16th to 19th September 1982; Music Department, Rhodes University, 7th to 8th October 1983 |publisher=Institute of Social and Economic Research |location=Grahamstown |editor-link=Andrew Tracey |editor-first=Andrew |editor-last=Tracey |oclc=13658380 |isbn=086810096X}}\n\n==Discography==\n{{See also|Juluka#Discography|Savuka#Selected music}}\n\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; width:10px;\"|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; width:320px;\"|Album\n!  style=\"text-align:center; width:20px;\"|Peak positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font