ay 25, 2017, [[Universal Pictures]] and DreamWorks Animation announced that a sequel is set to be released on March 26, 2021, with [[Alec Baldwin]] reprising his role.<ref name=\"sequel\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/05/boss-baby-2-alec-baldwin-release-date-dreamworks-animation-universal-1202102742/|title=Alec Baldwin Returns In \u2018The Boss Baby 2\u2019, Crawling To Theaters In 2021|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=May 25, 2017}}</ref> On May 17, 2019, it was announced that [[Tom McGrath (animator)|Tom McGrath]] will return as director and Jeff Hermann, who produces ''[[Bilby (film)|Bilby]]'' and ''[[Bird Karma]]'', as well as the upcoming short ''Marooned'', will produce the sequel.<ref>https://www.cartoonbrew.com/feature-film/boss-baby-2-will-be-tom-mcgraths-sixth-feature-film-at-dreamworks-174259.html</ref>\n\n===Television series===\n{{Main|The Boss Baby: Back in Business}}\nOn December 12, 2017, both [[Netflix]] and DreamWorks Animation announced the release of the TV series based off the film. ''[[The Boss Baby: Back in Business]]'' was released in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/she-ra-reboot-boss-baby-trolls-netflix-dreamworks/|title= \u2018She-Ra\u2019 Reboot, \u2018Boss Baby\u2019 Score Netflix Series Through DreamWorks Animation |date=December 12, 2017|accessdate=January 7, 2018|work=[[TheWrap]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|The Boss Baby}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.dreamworks.com/movies/the-boss-baby}}\n* [http://www.foxmovies.com/movies/the-boss-baby/ ''The Boss Baby''] at [[20th Century Fox|Fox Movies]]\n* {{IMDb title|3874544}}\n* {{bcdb title|166816}}\n* {{Rotten-tomatoes|boss_baby|The Boss Baby}}\n* {{Mojo title|bossbaby|The Boss Baby}}\n\n{{DreamWorks animated films}}\n{{Tom McGrath}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Boss Baby\n\n| image          = The Boss Baby poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Tom McGrath (animator)|Tom McGrath]]\n| producer       = [[Ramsey Ann Naito]]\n| writer         = [[Michael McCullers]]\n| based on       = {{based on|''The Boss Baby''|[[Marla Frazee]]}}\n| starring       = [[Alec Baldwin]]<br/>[[Steve Buscemi]]<br/>[[Jimmy Kimmel]]<br/>[[Lisa Kudrow]]<br/>Miles Bakshi\n| narrator       = [[Tobey Maguire]]\n| music          = [[Hans Zimmer]]<br/>Steve Mazzaro\n| cinematography = \n| editing        = James Ryan\n| studio         = [[DreamWorks Animation]]\n| distributor    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[20th Century Fox]]\n** (Worldwide)\n* [[Universal Pictures]]\n** (Japan)\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2017|3|12|[[Miami International Film Festival|Miami]]|2017|3|31|United States|2018|4|19|[[Norway]]}} \n| runtime        = 97 minutes<ref>{{cite web|title=The Boss Baby|url= https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/boss-baby-film-0|publisher=British Board of Film Classification|accessdate=March 9, 2017}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $125 million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/boss-baby-second-weekend-box-office-tops-beauty-beast/|title=The Boss Baby Tops Beauty and the Beast at Box Office for Second Week |work=[[Screen Rant]]|date=April 9, 2017|accessdate=January 31, 2018}}</ref>\n| gross          = $528 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url= https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=bossbaby.htm |title=The Boss Baby (2017) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| border         = yes\n}}\n'''''The Boss Baby''''' is a 2017 American [[Computer animation|computer-animated]] [[comedy film]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertainment.ie/cinema/movie-reviews/the-boss-baby-5440|title=The Boss Baby - Cinema, Movie, Film Review|first=Deirdre|last=Molumby|website=Entertainment.ie}}</ref> produced by [[DreamWorks Animation]] and distributed by [[20th Century Fox]]. Loosely based on the 2010 picture book of the same name by [[Marla Frazee]],<ref name=THRBaldwinSpacey /> the film was directed by [[Tom McGrath (animator)|Tom McGrath]], from a screenplay by [[Michael McCullers]], and stars the voices of [[Alec Baldwin]] as the title character, along with Miles Bakshi, [[Steve Buscemi]], [[Jimmy Kimmel]], [[Lisa Kudrow]], and [[Tobey Maguire]]. The plot follows a 7 year old boy helping his baby brother who is a secret agent in the war for adults' love between babies and puppies.\n\n''The Boss Baby'' premiered at the [[Miami International Film Festival]] on March 12, 2017, and was released on March 31.<ref name=THRShowmanPushed>{{cite news|last1=McClintock|first1=Pamela|title=Hugh Jackman's 'Greatest Showman on Earth' Pushed a Year to Christmas 2017|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/hugh-jackmans-greatest-showman-earth-824884|accessdate=September 19, 2015|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=September 18, 2015}}</ref> Upon release, the film received mixed reviews from critics and grossed $528 million worldwide against its $125 million budget. The film received Best Animated Feature nominations at the [[90th Academy Awards|Academy Awards]], [[Annie Awards]], and [[75th Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globes]] (losing all to ''[[Coco (2017 film)|Coco]]'').<ref name=\"Oscars\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/golden-globe-nominations-2018-nominees-full-list-1202634435/|title=Golden Globe Nominations: Complete List|work=Variety|date=December 11, 2017|accessdate=December 11, 2017|first=Rebecca|last=Rubin}}</ref>\n\nA sequel is scheduled to be released on March 26, 2021, while a [[Netflix]] TV series, ''[[The Boss Baby: Back in Business]]'', premiered April 6, 2018.\n\n==Plot==\nA boy named Tim Templeton tells a story about his 7-year-old self and his parents, Ted and Janice. One day, Tim is surprised when an infant wearing a business suit arrives at his house in a taxi, and Ted and Janice call him Tim's little brother. Tim is envious of the attention the day-old baby receives, not to mention suspicion when the infant acts odd around him, but his parents are oblivious.\n\nSoon, Tim learns that the baby can talk like an adult, and he introduces himself as \"The Boss\". Seeing an opportunity to get rid of him, Tim decides to record a conversation between the Boss Baby and other toddlers who are at Tim's house for a meeting. A chase ensues, and the [[Compact cassette|cassette tape]] is terminated by passing automobile after the Boss Baby threatens to tear up Tim's favorite stuffed animal, Lam-Lam. With no evidence to support him, Tim's parents ground him for three weeks.\n\nThe Boss Baby apologizes to Tim and has him suck on a pacifier that transports them to Baby Corp., a place where infants with adult-like minds work to preserve infant love everywhere. The Boss Baby explains that he was sent to see why puppies are being loved more than infants. He has infiltrated Tim's residence because his parents work for Puppy Co., which will unleash a new puppy on a pet convention in Las Vegas. The Boss Baby stays intelligent by drinking a \"Secret Baby Formula\" that enables a baby to act like an adult. However, should a baby not drink it after a period of time, he or she becomes a regular baby. When they overhear Boss Baby's boss threatening to fire him for not bringing in information, which would strip him of his formula and strand him at the Templetons, he and Tim agree to work together to prevent that.\n\nTim's parents \"un-ground\" him and take them to Puppy Co. for take your child to work day. While there, they slip away and find what they think is the plans for a \"Forever Puppy\", but they are captured by the company's founder and CEO, Francis E. Francis. They discover that Francis used to be the head of Baby Corp. and whom Boss Baby idolizes, but was ousted when it was discovered that his [[lactose intolerance]] kept the secret formula from working properly. Francis intends to have the Forever Puppies overshadow babies by stealing Boss Baby's serum bottle and infecting the puppies with it as revenge. Tim's parents go with Francis to Las Vegas, and Francis has his brother Eugene pose as Tim and Boss Baby's babysitter to keep them from interfering.\n\nWithout a steady flow of formula to maintain his intelligence, Boss Baby starts becoming a normal baby. Despite this, he and Tim evade the \"babysitter\" long enough to reach the airport but are too late to intercept Tim's parents. They sneak on to another plane bound for Las Vegas. There, they stall Francis' presentation when Eugene unwittingly gives away their plan. Furious at their interference, Francis locks Tim's parents up so he can burn them with exhaust from a rocket used to launch the Forever Puppies. Tim and Boss Baby defeat Eugene and move on to save their parents but are intercepted by Francis. Tim and Boss Baby push him off a ledge, making Francis tumble into the formula. Boss Baby opens the rocket to let the puppies out so they can save Tim's parents. His return to baby state is complete while on the rocket, and begins to cry, but Tim sings to him with [[Blackbird (Beatles song)|the family song]] to show his appreciation, causing him to jump off the rocket before it launches. After the rocket does launch, Tim takes Boss Baby to the formula vat and he returns to his original self. Francis then emerges from the vat, having been reverted to an obese baby and tries to attack Boss Baby, but is picked up by a redeemed Eugene and tells Tim and Boss Baby that \"This time we'll raise him right\".\n\nBoss Baby is promoted and leaves. Tim goes back to being an only child, but he and Boss Baby miss each other. After Tim writes a letter convincing him to live with him as his brother, Boss Baby returns to the Templeton family as a regular baby named Theodore Lindsey \"Ted\" Templeton. Back in the present, Tim finished with his brother Ted the story to his daughter, which she just had recently a baby sister, who acts like Ted did when he was Boss Baby.\n\n==Voice cast==\n[[File:Alec Baldwin (28246306070).jpg|thumb|right|Alec Baldwin at the 2016 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]]]\n* Miles Bakshi as Tim Templeton, Boss Baby's 7-year-old brother.<ref name=\"SFLikeGlenRoss\">{{cite web|last1=Amderton|first1=Ethan|title=DreamWorks Animation\u2019s \u2018The Boss Baby\u2019 Is Like an Animated \u2018Glengarry Glen Ross\u2019 for Kids (Comic-Con 2016)|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/boss-baby-comic-con/|publisher=/Film|accessdate=October 28, 2016|date=July 21, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"THRKimmelKudrowOswalt\" /><ref name=\"VarietyAnnecyBossBaby\">{{cite news|last1=Hopewell|first1=John|last2=Mayorga|first2=Emilio|title=Annecy: Tom McGrath Unveils Alec Baldwin-Starrer \u2018Boss Baby\u2019|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/annecy-tom-mcgrath-alec-baldwin-boss-baby-1201797075/|accessdate=June 18, 2016|work=Variety|date=June 16, 2016}}</ref>\n** [[Tobey Maguire]] as Adult Tim, the narrator.<ref name=\"USATSneakPeek\">{{cite news|last1=Alexander|first1=Bryan|title=Sneak peek: Alec Baldwin is 'The Boss Baby'|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2016/10/16/alec-baldwin-boss-baby-sneak-peek-exclusive/92058380/|accessdate=October 17, 2016|work=USA Today|date=October 17, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Alec Baldwin]] as Theodore Templeton / Boss Baby, a baby with the mind of an adult, who works at Baby Corp.<ref name=THRBaldwinSpacey />\n* [[Jimmy Kimmel]] as Ted Templeton, Janice's husband and Tim's father.<ref name=\"THRKimmelKudrowOswalt\" />\n* [[Lisa Kudrow]] as Janice Templeton, Ted's wife and Tim's mother.<ref name=\"THRKimmelKudrowOswalt\" />\n* [[Steve Buscemi]] as Francis E. Francis, the [[chief executive officer|CEO]] of Puppy Co and the former CEO of BabyCorp and Boss Baby's nemesis<ref name=\"THRKimmelKudrowOswalt\">{{cite news|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|title=Jimmy Kimmel, Lisa Kudrow, Patton Oswalt Join Voicecast of 'Boss Baby' (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/jimmy-kimmel-lisa-kudrow-patton-901570|accessdate=June 16, 2016|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=June 13, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Conrad Vernon]] as Eugene Francis, Francis E. Francis' brother and minion.\n* James McGrath as Wizzie, Tim's [[Gandalf]]-esque alarm clock.\n* [[David Soren (animator)|David Soren]] as Jimbo\n* Nina Zoe Bakshi as Tim's Daughter\n* [[Tom McGrath (animator)|Tom McGrath]] as TV Chef\n* [[Walt Dohrn]] as Photographer\n* James Ryan as Story Bear\n* Eric Bell Jr. as Triplets\n* ViviAnn Yee as Staci\n* [[Edie Mirman]] as The Big Boss Baby, Boss Baby's big boss.\n* James McGrath and Joseph Izzo as [[Elvis Presley|Elvis]] Impersonators\n\n==Production==\nUpon reading the original book on which the film is based McGrath felt a connection to it, as he had an older brother and felt like \"the boss baby of the family\".<ref name=\"Bossstanford\">{{cite web|last1=Popp|first1=Olivia|title=\u2018The Boss Baby\u2019 director and producer on life, laughs and a love for animation|url=https://www.stanforddaily.com/2017/03/28/final-cv-interview-the-boss-baby-director-and-producer-on-life-laughs-and-a-love-for-animation/|website=The Stanford Daily|accessdate=23 December 2017}}</ref> In keeping with that theme he stated, in an interview with Den of Geek, that \"My personal goal with this was to watch this movie with my brother, and to see how it affected him!\", which resulted in McGrath's brother being moved to tears by the completed film.<ref name=\"DOGBOSS\">{{cite web|title=Tom McGrath interview: Boss Baby, animation, George Lucas|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/uk/movies/boss-baby/48487/tom-mcgrath-interview-boss-baby-animation-george-lucas|website=Den of Geek|accessdate=23 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe look of the film was inspired by design techniques popularized in the 1960s,<ref name=\"CartoonBBoss\">{{cite web|last1=Failes|first1=Ian|title=Drawing On Classic References, \u2018Boss Baby\u2019 Director Tom McGrath Explores A Fresh Look|url=http://www.cartoonbrew.com/interviews/drawing-classic-references-boss-baby-director-tom-mcgrath-explores-fresh-look-149528.html|website=Cartoon Brew|accessdate=23 December 2017}}</ref> as well as animated films from both 60s and 50s.<ref name=\"Bossstanford\"/> This was due to McGrath's belief that contemporary animated films focused too much on realism. To help his staff McGrath would play the opening scene of ''[[Lady and the Tramp]]'' for new hires specifically noting that the film \"should be easy on the eyes and really lead your eye to what\u2019s important in the shot.<ref name=\"CartoonBBoss\"/>\n\n[[File:Tom McGrath by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg|thumb|Director Tom McGrath at the 2016 [[San Diego Comic-Con International|San Diego Comic-Con]]|175px]]\nIn September 2014, [[Alec Baldwin]] and [[Kevin Spacey]] joined the cast of the film,<ref name=THRBaldwinSpacey>{{cite news|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|title=Alec Baldwin and Kevin Spacey to Voice Star in DreamWorks Animation's 'Boss Baby'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/alec-baldwin-kevin-spacey-voice-736795|accessdate=October 15, 2014|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=September 30, 2014}}</ref> with further casting news announced in June 2016, including [[Steve Buscemi]] replacing Spacey.<ref>{{cite news|title=Boss Baby: Jimmy Kimmel, Lisa Kudrow, Steve Buscemi added to voice cast|last1=Robinson|first1=Will|url=https://ew.com/article/2016/06/13/boss-baby-jimmy-kimmel-lisa-kudrow-dreamworks/|accessdate=January 13, 2017|publisher=ew.com|date=June 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nMiles Bakshi, son of the DreamWorks Animation's producer [[Gina Shay]] and grandson of the film director [[Ralph Bakshi]], who directed the 1972 American adult animated comedy film ''[[Fritz the Cat (film)|Fritz the Cat]]'', provided the voice of 7-year old Tim. Having been often present at DreamWorks, McGrath initially asked Bakshi only to provide a temporary voice for Tim to see if the character \"worked\". The producers listened to 30 to 40 children to choose the scratch voice. McGrath explained their decision: \"No one sounded as authentic as Miles did. A lot of child actors are great, but they are over-articulate for their age. Miles was just natural and charming. He had a little slur to his voice at the time and it was very endearing.\" Three years later, Miles was told that he got the part.<ref>{{cite news|last1=King|first1=Susan|title=Miles Bakshi continues a family animation tradition with 'The Boss Baby'|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-boss-baby-bakshi-20170328-story.html|accessdate=May 21, 2017|work=Los Angeles Times|date=March 29, 2017}}</ref> Bakshi was 10 when he began recording the voice. During the long process, his voice started to change and \"by the end it got pretty tough\", according to Bakshi, who was 14 when the film was released. He had to get his voice \"very soft, but when I got that perfect tone it was great.\"\n\n==Music==\nThe film was scored by [[Hans Zimmer]], along with Steve Mazzaro and various artists. The film's soundtrack was released on [[Back Lot Music]] & iTunes. \"[[Blackbird (Beatles song)|Blackbird]]\" by [[The Beatles]] is used as part of the plot at various points throughout the film.<ref name=\"blackbird\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-boss-baby-2017|title=Review - The Boss Baby|first=Susan|last=Wloszczyna|date=March 28, 2017|accessdate=April 2, 2017|publisher=RogerEbert.com}}</ref> During the end credits, Missi Hale recorded a cover of the [[Burt Bacharach]] song [[What The World Needs Now Is Love]] (first performed by [[Jackie DeShannon]]). \"[[My House (Flo Rida song)|My House]]\" by [[Flo Rida]] is also used in the trailer for the film.\n\n==Release==\n''The Boss Baby'' was initially scheduled for release on March 18, 2016,<ref name=\"KFP3\">{{cite news|title='Kung Fu Panda 3' Moves Out of 2015 to Avoid 'Star Wars'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/kung-fu-panda-3-moves-756636|accessdate=December 11, 2014|newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter|date=December 11, 2014}}</ref> but was later pushed back to March 31, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Release Schedule - New Dates & Changes |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/schedule/?view=changes&p=.htm |publisher=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=June 20, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160620172930/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/schedule/?view=changes&p=.htm |archivedate=June 20, 2016 |url-status=unfit }}</ref> The film premiered at the [[Miami International Film Festival|Miami Film Festival]] on March 12, 2017,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Boss Baby|url=http://2017.miamifilmfestival.com/films/the-boss-baby/|publisher=Miami Film Festival|accessdate=March 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hazelton|first1=John|title='The Boss Baby': Review|url=http://www.screendaily.com/reviews/the-boss-baby-review/5115763.article|accessdate=March 18, 2017|work=Screen Daily|date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> and was released in the United States on March 31, 2017, by [[20th Century Fox]].<ref name=THRShowmanPushed /> The film was later released in Japan on March 21, 2018 by DreamWorks Animation's sister company [[Universal Pictures]]. The Japanese release is accompanied by the DreamWorks animated short ''[[Bird Karma]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Amidi |first=Amid |date=November 15, 2017 |title=Dreamworks Is Going To Start Adding Shorts In Front Of Its Theatrical Films|url=https://www.cartoonbrew.com/shorts/dreamworks-going-start-adding-shorts-front-theatrical-films-154635.html |work=[[Cartoon Brew]] |location= |access-date=December 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''The Boss Baby'' was released on Digital HD on July 4, 2017, and was released on DVD, Blu-ray, [[Blu-ray 3D]] and [[Ultra HD Blu-ray]] on July 25, 2017 by [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]]. The releases also include a new short film, ''The Boss Baby and Tim's Treasure Hunt Through Time''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Milligan|first1=Mercedes|title=\u2018Boss Baby\u2019 Gets Home Delivery in July|url=http://www.animationmagazine.net/home-entertainment/boss-baby-gets-home-delivery-in-july/|accessdate=May 25, 2017|work=Animation Magazine|date=May 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''The Boss Baby'' grossed $175 million in the United States and Canada and $352.9 million in other territories for a worldwide total of $527.9 million.<ref name=BOM/>\n\nIn North America, ''The Boss Baby'' opened alongside ''[[Ghost in the Shell (2017 film)|Ghost in the Shell]]'' and ''[[The Zookeeper's Wife (film)|The Zookeeper's Wife]]'', and was initially projected to gross around $30 million from 3,773 theaters in its opening weekend.<ref name=preview>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/boss-baby-and-ghost-in-the-shell-to-take-on-beauty-and-the-beast-this-weekend/ |title=\u2018Boss Baby,\u2019 \u2018Ghost in the Shell\u2019 to Battle \u2018Beauty and the Beast\u2019 This Weekend |date=March 29, 2017 |work=[[TheWrap]]}}</ref> However, after grossing $1.5 million from Thursday night previews and $15.5 million on Friday, weekend projections were increased to $50 million. It ended up debuting to $50.2 million, finishing first at the box office.<ref name=opening>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/03/ghost-in-the-shell-scarlett-johansson-boss-baby-beauty-and-the-beast-weekend-box-office-1202056616/ |title=\u2018Boss Baby\u2019 Cleans \u2018Beauty And The Beast\u2019s Clock With $51M+ Opening; \u2018Ghost\u2019 Shell-Shocked At $20M+ |accessdate=April 2, 2017 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref> It remained atop the box office in its second weekend, grossing $26.3 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/04/smurfs-the-lost-village-going-in-style-boss-baby-beauty-and-the-beast-box-office-1202064314/ |title=\u2018Boss Baby\u2019 Crawls Ahead Of \u2018Beauty\u2019 With $26M+; \u2018Smurfs\u2019 Lost In 3rd With $14M|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=April 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 52% based on 178 reviews and an average rating of 5.52/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"''The Boss Baby''{{'}}s talented cast, glimmers of wit, and flashes of visual inventiveness can't make up for a thin premise and a disappointing willingness to settle for doody jokes.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=The Boss Baby (2017)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_boss_baby|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 50 out of 100 based on 32 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-boss-baby|title=The Boss Baby Reviews|work=[[Metacritic]]}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\u2212\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemascore.com/|title=Home - Cinemascore|work=cinemascore.com}}</ref>\n\n[[Neil Genzlinger]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' praised Baldwin and the adult humor, saying: \"The contrast between the helpless-infant stage of life and corporate-speak is funny but fairly high-concept for a kiddie movie, and the plot grows denser as it goes along and the baby and Tim reluctantly join forces to stop a conspiracy by which puppies would corner all the love in the world.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uproxx.com/movies/beauty-and-the-beast-review/ |title=Review: \u2018The Boss Baby\u2019 Puts Alec Baldwin in Diapers, Sort Of |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 30, 2017|accessdate=April 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width: 99%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Date of ceremony\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\" | Recipients\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Academy Awards]]\n| [[90th Academy Awards|March 4, 2018]]\n| [[Academy Award for Best Animated Feature|Best Animated Feature]]\n| [[Tom McGrath (animator)|Tom McGrath]] and Ramsey Ann Naito\n| {{